<HEAD>Activists Say U.S. Navy Turned Water Hoses On Anti-Nuke Protesters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three anti-nuclear protesters were arrested for trying to cling to the hull of a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> frigate, and activists charged Tuesday that crew members turned high-powered water hoses on the demonstrators. The protesters, who were in rubber dinghies,, were charged with disorderly conduct after the incident Monday. They tried to hang onto the hull of the <ORGANIZATION> USS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewton </ORGANIZATION>, which was moored near <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> off the southern coast of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. Cmdr. <PERSON> Kraig </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, the <PERSON> Brewton </PERSON>'s commander, said hoses were turned on the protesters because they planned to deface the vessel with spray paint. Earlier, the three attached a banner to the ship. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said the action may have been `` heavy-handed'' but that every precaution was taken to prevent injury. <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> <PERSON> Vallentine </PERSON>, a member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and an activist in the Party for Nuclear Disarmament, demanded an apology, saying one protester was treated at a hospital for an eye injury and facial bruises. ` I believe it is the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> that should be charged with disorderly conduct,'' she told reporters after a meeting with <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>.
