<HEAD>Teacher Walkouts Affect Schools In Five States</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Nationally, walkouts ... and 21st graf,
`Louisiana: A ..., to UPDATE with Louisiana strike settled.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Teachers carried picket signs in more than 20 public school districts in four states Tuesday. Many held out for raises, and the biggest pay demand, 42 percent over three years, drew the ire of a mayor as `` irresponsible.'' `` The teachers decided it's time to take a stand and that stand actually is a walk and that's what we'll be doing tomorrow morning: walking a picket line,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Grady </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lowell </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, after a unanimous strike vote there Tuesday. The first day of school was canceled Wednesday for the city's 13,100 pupils. Nationally, walkouts affected more than 100,000 pupils in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. A strike in its third week in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> was settled Tuesday night. More than 1,400 professors and academic staff members at <ORGANIZATION> Wayne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> also went on strike Tuesday over union work rules and salary. University president <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamany </PERSON> predicted classes for the roughly 30,000 students would continue with other full-time and part-time instructors, but professors said they expected few classes to be held. An additional 950 clerical workers and secretaries represented by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> have been on strike at <ORGANIZATION> Wayne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> since Aug. 25. In <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, bargainers representing 991 teachers met with school officials through the weekend with no success. Major issues were class size and salary, with teachers asking for a 10 percent raise and being offered 2 percent, <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Colleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudgens </PERSON> said. Superintendent <PERSON> LaBarbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Gragg </PERSON> said Monday night that talks would be scheduled later in the week. Meanwhile, classes that opened Sept. 1 were canceled Tuesday for <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION>'s 17,284 students as teachers picketed, Deputy Superintendent <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> Love </PERSON> said. In State College, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, 415 teachers staged the first strike in the district's history, said union spokesman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Apaliski </PERSON>. About 5,900 students missed the scheduled opening day of school Tuesday. `` We are not at all close,'' district spokeswoman <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Best </PERSON> said. `` It's very discouraging.'' The school board offered a 33 percent raise over three years, Ms. <PERSON> Best </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has not made public its pay demand. In <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, teachers in nearly 40 school districts are going to work this week without a contract. The only strike votes taken, however, were in <LOCATION> Lowell </LOCATION> and Peabody. Teacher strikes are illegal in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. Officials canceled the first day of school for 13,100 pupils Wednesday in <LOCATION> Lowell </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, after the district's 970 teachers voted unanimously to strike for more pay and to preserve longevity bonuses. In Peabody, the city's 408 teachers rejected a 17 percent wage increase over three years and held out for 42 percent over the same time span. `` To sit at the table locked in at 42 percent is totally irresponsible,'' said Peabody Mayor <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Torigian </PERSON>. School Superintendent <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON> said administrators were trying to bring in enough substitutes to keep classes going. <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Latessa </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> defended the union's position. The 42 percent wage request, <PERSON> Latessa </PERSON> said, is smaller than it appears because the teachers maintain that they have been performing extra duties such as elementary preparation and handling oversized classes without extra pay. Here was the picture by state-by-state: <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>: Strikes in 10 districts idled nearly 45,000 students and more than 2,000 teachers, the <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>: Strikes by about 2,200 teachers in nine districts affected about 36,000 students, according to <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Badner </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>: Strike votes by union representing 1,378 teachers affected two districts. <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>: Strikes in two districts affected 501 teachers and 9,145 pupils in <LOCATION> Granite </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Farmer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mansfield </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Bellflower </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>: About 600 teachers, joined by bus drivers, ended a strike Tuesday night after school officials agreed to collective bargaining in Vermilion Parish, where a 6 percent pay cut was imposed in 1987.
