<HEAD>Warmup for Hecht-Bryan Battle in Nevada; Florida Voters Narrow
Senate Field</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> voters were expected to set the stage today for Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>'s drive to oust Republican Sen. Chic <PERSON> Hecht </PERSON>, while six <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> Democrats and two Republicans fought over the seat of retiring Sen. <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hecht </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> faced only token opposition in today's primaries, and for months they have been attacking each other <PERSON> Hecht </PERSON>, who is seeking his second term, has criticized the governor as too pro-labor. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, in the middle of his second term, has charged <PERSON> Hecht </PERSON> with lacking credibility and being ineffective. A poll taken in August for the gaming industry showed <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> with a 14-point lead over <PERSON> Hecht </PERSON>, who six years ago narrowly defeated Democratic Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON> after the incumbent was implicated in a <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> union scandal. <PERSON> Hecht </PERSON> has stopped releasing his own poll results but said he is closing the gap and considers the race a toss-up. <PERSON> Hecht </PERSON>, whose voting record is extremely conservative, has become known for his occasional verbal miscues, once referring to a `` nuclear suppository'' when he meant `` repository.'' A recent survey of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> administrative assistants ranked him as the least effective senator in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hecht </PERSON>'s only primary opponent is <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Scheffler </PERSON>, 38-year-old owner of a graphics business in <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> who said he would press for reprocessing nuclear waste brought to <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> so that only low-level, less radioactive waste would remain. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>'s opponents in the Democratic primary are <LOCATION> Manford </LOCATION> `` Cave Rock Manny'' <PERSON> Beals </PERSON>, <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kepler </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, a two-man Republican primary matched Rep. <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, grandson of the legendary <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> A's baseball manager, against former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON>, who successfully prosecuted Colombian cocaine kingpin <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivas </PERSON>. <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON> entered the race late, in June, and <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> was heavily favored in pre-election polls after outspending his rival by about $ 2.2 million to $ 100,000. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and former Marine Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> made appearances for <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, who has one of the most conservative records in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON> was frustrated by <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>'s refusal to debate, and emphasized that point by carrying around a life-size replica of <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> he called `` Cardboard Connie.'' `` If he debates me, he knows the jig's up,'' said <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON>. `` He'd be forced to discuss issues ... People would see the lights are on but nobody's home.'' <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> said <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON> was n't `` a viable candidate,'' and that there was no reason `` to have been drawn into his campaign. My feeling was that we should continue with delivery of the message we started with in October, talking about the importance of freedom, free markets, less taxes, freedom as an objective of foreign policy.'' For the Democrats, state Insurance Commissioner <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON> appeared to hold a wide lead, but not wide enough to win a majority and avoid an Oct. 4 runoff with the second-place finisher. Others in the race were Reps. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mica </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> `` Buddy'' McKay, state Sen. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, former Republican Gov. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> and former <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> postal clerk <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Rader </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON>, who lost to <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> in the 1980 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> race, raised $ 1 million within six weeks of announcing, and opponents noted he took at least $ 160,000 from the insurance industry he regulates. <PERSON> MacKay </PERSON> campaign manager <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON> called <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON>'s department `` a saga of sleaze. The early Democratic frontrunner, former Gov. <PERSON> Reubin </PERSON> <PERSON> Askew </PERSON>, quit the race in May, saying running for office had become too expensive. Democrats acknowledge that their crowded field and likely runoff may hurt their prospects in November. `` I do n't think it'll be an easy race, but I think it's winnable,'' said <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitehead </PERSON>
