<HEAD>Soviet Olympic Medalists Will Collect Cash in Seoul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviets athletes who win gold medals at the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Olympics will be awarded the equivalent of $ 19,000 for their efforts, the head of the Soviet Olympic Committee says. <PERSON> Marat </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramov </PERSON> announced the new policy at a news conference Monday and denied such payments conflict with the purely amateur status Soviet athletes purportedly possess. He said those on the 550-member Soviet team in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> who win gold medals will be paid 12,000 rubles -LRB- $ 19,047 -RRB-. Silver medalists will receive 5,000 rubles, and bronze medalists will collect 3,000 rubles. Those are handsome sums in a country where the average monthly wage for a factory worker is around 200 rubles. According to <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Dmitrieyev </PERSON>, deputy foreign editor of the daily newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Sovietsky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sport </ORGANIZATION>, the sums earmarked for <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> medalists will be the largest ever paid to Soviet victors in a Summer Games. `` If they received $ 100 in the past, it was considered a large sum,'' <PERSON> Dmitrieyev </PERSON> said in a telephone interview, referring to payments made to Soviet participants in the 1976 <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> and 1980 <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> games. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> did not take part in the 1984 Olympics, held in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. According to <PERSON> Dmitrieyev </PERSON>, Soviet winners at the 1988 <LOCATION> Calgary </LOCATION> Winter Olympics also received large sums to reward them for good performance. <PERSON> Gramov </PERSON> noted that 15 percent of the prize money paid to Soviet medalists will be in foreign currency. That is important because the Soviet ruble, which is not convertible into foreign currency, is useless abroad and can not buy the sort of Western consumer goods that many Soviets covet.
