<HEAD>Average Cost of Lawyer for Poor Defendant Now $223</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says it now costs an average of $ 223 to provide legal representation for a poor criminal defendant, and the number requiring such services has risen sharply since 1982. The <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> said Monday the $ 223 cost, the average in 1986, is up from $ 196 per case in 1982. The caseload rose to nearly 4.5 million, up about 40 percent from the 3.2 million cases four years earlier, the bureau said in a report. The 50 states and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, spent a combined $ 991 million for indigent defendants in 1986, compared to $ 625 million in 1982 _ an increase of 60 percent. The programs are financed by state, county and local governments in each state. The rights of poor criminal defendants to legal representation were spelled out in a number of <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings beginning in 1932. One case was the landmark <PERSON> Gideon </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wainright </PERSON> in 1963, when the court extended the right to counsel in state courts to all indigent defendants charged with a felony. Some states have expanded the program to include representation for proceedings involving parole, probation, parental rights, civil commitment and post-conviction matters. The department said <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> spent the least for indigent defendants _ an average of 69 cents per state resident. The District of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> spent the most, $ 29 per capita. The average per capita expenditure nationwide was $ 4.11 in 1986, up from $ 2.76 in 1982. When average costs per indigent case were computed, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> again was last, spending $ 63 per case in 1986. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> was first, spending an average of $ 540. There are three basic programs used to provide the legal services. Assigned counsel programs feature case-by-case appointments of lawyers; in contract programs, the government contracts with individual lawyers, law firms or local bar associations to provide services for a given period; and in public defender programs, a salaried staff is hired to provide legal services. The report was an update to a 1982 study on indigent defendants. Since the initial study, the report said, there was a movement from county to state financing; an increase in rates of compensation paid to private lawyers, and expanded use of contracts for providing representation to the poor. Here are the total state-by-state expenditures -LRB- including <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> -RRB- in 1986, in millions; the per capita expenditure in actual dollars; and the state's ranking in per capita spending: <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, $ 6.1 million, $ 1.52, 44; <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, $ 6.8 million, $ 12.91, 2; <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> $ 16.2 million, $ 4.89, 10; <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, $ 1.6 million, 69 cents, 51; <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, $ 251.5 million, $ 9.32, 3; <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, $ 12.1 million, $ 3.71, 21; <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, $ 9.2 million, $ 2.90, 25; <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, $ 2.7 million, $ 4.34, 14; <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>, $ 18 million, $ 28.90, 1; <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, $ 82.1 million, $ 7.03, 5. <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, $ 8.3 million, $ 1.36, 47; <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, $ 4.3 million, $ 4.13, 18; <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, $ 2.6 million, $ 2.62, 28; <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, $ 33.1 million, $ 2.87, 26; <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, $ 10.9 million, $ 1.99, 37; <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, $ 11.5 million, $ 4.05, 20; <LOCATION> K