<HEAD>Time Running Out on Environmental Bills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has left itself about a month to solve major environmental problems that have eluded solution in the 1980s _ redoubling the battle against urban air pollution and launching an attack on acid rain. Lawmakers return to town Wednesday, shooting for an early October adjournment. As the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> enter the home stretch, clean air legislation is barely out of the starting gate. Neither chamber has even scheduled debate on the Clean Air Act revisions that are being watched closely by some 100 cities and metropolitan areas that failed to meet last December's deadline for bringing ozone and carbon monoxide levels within national health standards. A comprehensive package to control urban smog, acid rain and airborne toxic chemicals was ready for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> debate last November, but it has been stalled by a variety of opponents, most notably Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. The package's principal sponsor, Sen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, has been trying to negotiate floor time with <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> has said that if necessary, he will offer his air bill as an amendment to must-pass legislation. In the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, serious closed-door negotiations among leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> did n't begin until this summer, leaving little time to get a complicated proposal ready for the floor. Any package produced by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would most likely give cities more time to clean up their air but also require tougher actions to combat pollution, from local driving restrictions to stricter emissions standards for vehicles. Debate, a good bit of it in scientific terms, centers on how much more time will be granted and just what corrective steps will be required. A complicating factor is that the nation has already employed the measures that can bring large and quick reductions in pollution. Acid rain control is simpler scientifically but far more complicated economically and geographically. Acid rain, a byproduct of coal-burning factories and power plants, is a major concern of the East, which is downwind from the industrial <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. Just who pays to clean up Midwestern emissions is a major question, with many Western lawmakers cool to a national subsidy for Midwestern cleanup costs. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> not only has power plants in his state that would have to reduce their emissions, his state has huge deposits of high sulfur coal that could lose its market to cleaner burning coal from other states under an acid rain control bill. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has a fallback option if it fails to produce clean air legislation. It can, as it did last December, pass another stopgap bill that would prevent the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> from taking action against areas not meeting the standards. The environment surfaced as an issue last week in the presidential race between Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> claimed to be highly committed to a cleaner environment, although the record of the Reagan-Bush administration has been given dismal marks by environmental groups. The clean air fight is at the top of the environment-conservation agenda for the 100th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, but other issues are vying for attention in the closing weeks of the election-year session. One that might not take much time is the early 1987 request by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and the oil industry to allow petroleum exploration in the <ORGANIZATION> Arctic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s north coast The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> and Fisheries committees have endorsed drilling bills, but the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, where the environmental lobby has more clout, is sitting on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill. Likely to emerge from <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> after a four-year struggle is a renewal of the Endangered Species Act authorizing a 50 percent increase in program spending in the early 1990s. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is also ready to pass a $ 9.8 billion fiscal 1989 spending bill for the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and other land and resource agencies. It is drawing veto threats because it would delay spending for clean-coal technology research and bar oil leasing off portions of the coasts of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. House and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators are putting the finishing touches on legislation that would encourage the use of less-polluting methanol, ethanol and natural gas as alternatives to imported petroleum for powering vehicles. Awaiting Senate action are House-passed bills that would reorganize the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to make its director independent of political appointees in the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>; cut back on commercial timbering in the <ORGANIZATION> Tongass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>; and prevent a shopping center from being built adjacent to the <LOCATION> Manassas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Battlefield </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> in northern <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>.
