<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After a week of refining his message and selling it to friendly audiences, <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential nominee <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> is home preparing for the fall campaign following a patriotic season opener at the Statue of Liberty. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> is spending time with his family today and holds staff meetings Wednesday before taking a quick swing to <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> at week's end. The <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator delivered a Labor Day tribute Monday to the Pledge of Allegiance, which the Republicans have attempted to turn into a political weapon against <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> blasted <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for vetoing a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> bill that would have penalized teachers who did not lead their students in the pledge. The values embodied in the pledge `` deserve to be transmitted to our children,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. `` To us, they are not hokey or cornball or passe,'' he said. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> also toured <LOCATION> Ellis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, where millions of immigrants entered the country and which is now undergoing restoration. The Quayles are of Scottish descent and their relatives did not come through <LOCATION> Ellis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. But the couple and their three children posed for photographs anyway with a group of people dressed in costumes of their native countries. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s speech at the base of <LOCATION> Lady </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Liberty </LOCATION>, with the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> skyline in the background and <LOCATION> Ellis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> nearby, was planned as a moving kickoff to the countdown to Election Day. But it was disrupted briefly by about