<HEAD>New Police Hauls Aways Protesters Remembering `Red Terror'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Paramilitary police, some carrying truncheons, broke up a demonstration and arrested protesters marking the 70th anniversary of the launching of a Bolshevik campaign to stifle political opposition. At least 100 police officers, occasionally aided by civilian auxiliary police, also detained some pedestrians who shouted that the arrests were `` a disgrace.'' Monday's demonstration was on the 70th anniversary of the `` Red Terror,'' the Bolshevik campaign that decreed `` class enemies'' should be put in concentration camps and political opponents shot. The demonstration in downtown Pushkin Square was called by the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, an unofficial political group. Reporters saw five people arrested and put into buses. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, the official news agency, said 17 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> were detained and a court would decide punishment. <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Mityunov </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said none of the members had been in touch with him by late Monday, and interpreted that to mean they still were in jail. During the demonstration, police hauled away an elderly woman and arrested a man after he put a black ribbon over his mouth, apparently to symbolize that authorities prevented freedom of speech. It was not clear whether the man or the woman belonged to the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. More than 100 people gathered around the woman as she spoke of being jailed and sent to internal exile years ago. When a police officer yelled `` Disperse!'' a column of about 50 policemen forced the crowd aside and grabbed the woman. The <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> called the demonstration to remember the `` Red Terror,'' which bega