<FIRST>r i PM-Swaziland     09-06 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Swaziland,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kingdom Marks 20 Years Of Independence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MBABANE, Swaziland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ruled by the world's youngest monarch, tiny <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION> marked 20 years of independence today as a nation rich in tradition and largely free of the turbulence that plagues its neighbors. Wedged between <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, this kingdom of rolling hills and lush valleys has spent the past two decades pursuing both Western-style modernization and preservation of age-old customs. Progress means a new <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> bottling plant in the capital of <LOCATION> Mbabane </LOCATION>, video cassette recorders in the expanding shops and luxury tourist hotels. Tradition, meanwhile, calls for regular celebrations with singing and dancing by bare-breasted maidens in tribute to 20-year-old spear-wielding King <PERSON> Mswati </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and his mother, known as the Great She Elephant. For these festive occasions, including a nine-hour independence celebration planned today at the country's main stadium, both men and women appear in traditional red, orange and yellow skirts, with long strands of beads and feathers in their hair. The men carry animal skin shields, the women wear beehive hairnets. The baby-faced king, who already has four wives, was barely four months old when his nation received independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> on Sept. 6, 1968. Two years ago, he replaced his father, the late <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Sobhuza </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, who ruled for 62 years and had at least 68 sons. Economically, landlocked <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION> remains an agricultural nation heavily dependent on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, which borders it on three sides. Thousands of Swazi men work in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s mines and the vast majority of <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION>'s imports reach the country via its powerful neighbor. A handful of foreign firms that disinvested from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> _ such as <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> _ have moved their plants to <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION>. Another approach has been for firms in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to falsely label their goods as `` Made in <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION>'' to evade embargoes against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> has received `` Made in <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION>'' wine, even though there are no vineyards in <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION>. Citrus produce amounting to four times <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION>'s annual output has turned up with Swazi labels in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION>'s eastern neighbor, <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, offers access to the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> and alternatives to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> transport routes. But <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>'s main contribution at present is an unwelcome one _ more than 100,000 refugees who have fled into <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION> from famine and civil war in their country. <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION>, half the size of <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, has two refugee centers designed to hold just a few thousand people. Aside from the refugees, who swell the country's population by about 15 percent, <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION> is ethnically homogenous and has avoided the inter-tribal strife that has plagued many other African countries. The relatively few indidents of political violence in recent years generally have involved anti-apartheid activists and guerrillas from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, who on occasion have been targets of cross-border raids and kidnappings by South African agents. The king and the royal family have the final say on all major matters. But most day-to-day business is left in the hands of the Cabinet, <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and the bureaucracy, which conduct the political affairs with a distinctive <LOCATION> Swazi </LOCATION> touch. When the parliamentary electoral college was selected last November, members were chosen by voters who passed through cattle gates next to the candidate of their choice. When retired white farmer <PERSON> Rex </PERSON> <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON> and his wife arrived to vote, policemen grabbed him, placed him at a gate and told him he had been chosen as a candidate. While being whisked away for week-long private consultations with the other winners, <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON> shouted to his wife to bring his heart tablets and cigarettes from home.
