<HEAD>Amnesty: Human Rights Improved In Cuba, But Critics Still Jailed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The communist leaders of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> continue to imprison citizens who speak out against them, but have also taken significant steps toward improving human rights, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> says in a report today. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s recent release of large numbers of political prisoners, improvement of prison conditions and limiting of the scope of the death penalty were welcomed by the international human rights organization. However, laws that have been used to stifle opposition and jail `` prisoners of conscience'' remain in force and seriously threaten government critics, it said. The report was written after a three-member team led by Amnesty Secretary-General <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> in March for the first time since 1977. The group repeated its longstanding appeal to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> for the unconditional release of prisoners of conscience, people jailed for their political or religious beliefs. Many recently released prisoners have been forced to leave <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, it said. Most political prisoners were charged with `` enemy propaganda'' after writing or saying things the government disapproved of, sometimes in private letters sent abroad or to foreign embassies in <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Amnesty </PERSON> said. It said others were convicted of trying to leave <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> without permission or of insulting behavior toward state officials. The group believes others were sentenced for politically related criminal offenses `` where there is reason to believe that they may have been convicted solely on account of their peaceful opposition to the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> government,'' the report said. Amnesty urged the <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> government to speed up a promised review of hundreds of political prisoners and expressed concern about their ability to obtain a proper defense and trial. It said the `` steady pace'' of recent releases of political prisoners made it difficult to estimate how many are still held in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. As of early August, about 250 prisoners were being held for crimes against state security and an unknown number _ believed to be in the hundreds _ were held under other sections of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s penal code used to restrict basic rights, particularly the internationally recognized right to leave one's country, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> said. The Amnesty team met senior <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> security and legal officials, visited two prisons holding political prisoners and interviewed dozens of prisoners in private, the report said. It said political inmates in the two prisons, <ORGANIZATION> Combinado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> del </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Este </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Boniato </PERSON>, were in the past reported to have been beaten, kept in poor conditions, given inadequate food and denied medical treatment. It said Cuban authorities told the visitors they were trying to improve the worst parts of these prisons. The report noted that improvements in physical conditions and the prison regime appear to have been introduced in the last eight months. However, <PERSON> Amnesty </PERSON> said prisoners do not feel confident of getting a fair hearing about complaints and fear retaliation. Amnesty said use of the death penalty appears to have been reduced considerably since the early 1980s. It quoted <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s justice minister as saying that although 216 people were executed between 1959 and 1987, the number executed since 1984 is 11, all for common crimes rather than security crimes.
