<HEAD>Moms, Children Reunited in Campout Behind Prison Gates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRI COLBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DWIGHT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wearing a yellow poncho in the steady rain, 10-year-old <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Nathaniel </PERSON> helped her mother stock their gray tent with camping supplies: sleeping bags, thin mattresses and a cooler. Outside the tent, beneath a cluster of sturdy oak trees, they had a clear view of the 12-foot fence, topped with a spiral of barbed wire, that surrounded them and the rest of the <ORGANIZATION> Dwight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correctional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>' only prison for women. But inside, at the start of an overnight campout for inmates and their children, they could ignore the fence, be alone and, if only for a few hours, do the things that mothers and daughters do. `` It gives me pleasure today to sleep with her, to comb her hair, to wash her,'' said <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Nathaniel </PERSON>, a convicted murderer. The campout on the last weekend of August was the last of three held over the summer at <LOCATION> Dwight </LOCATION>, located some 75 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. About 80 children and 36 inmates took part in the program, funded by a federal grant, said Warden <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Huch </PERSON>. The children arrived on a Saturday morning, stayed overnight in tents with their mothers and left the next day. Volleyball, crafts, a play performed by the prison drama club and an evening bonfire helped fill their time. The overnight visit gave <PERSON> Sheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Decker </PERSON>, 37, a chance to have some `` girl talk'' with her 17-year-old daughter, <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON>, but it did n't completely ease the pain of separation. `` When we look at each other and I know she's got to go beyond that fence, you know it hurts, and we know it for a minute but then we shrug it off and we go on,'' Ms. <PERSON> Decker </PERSON> said. `` We kind of play and get it up out of our system. But it's coming.'' For Ms. <PERSON> Decker </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Nathaniel </PERSON>, separation from their children is the hardest part of imprisonment. `` That is the punishment, that's it,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Nathaniel </PERSON>, who hopes to be paroled in 4 -LCB- years. But the visits help. Imprisonment means missing experiences that other mothers and daughters share, said Ms. <PERSON> Decker </PERSON>, who hopes to be paroled in three years from an 18-year term for armed violence. `` You go to sleep at night and you wake up and it's to the same thing every day,'' she said. `` It's not like being with your child and raising them and teaching them the facts of life, going through their first dating experience ... finding her first love.'' Ordinary visits can last from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m. on a weekday or until 7 p.m. on weekends, but Ms. <PERSON> Decker </PERSON> said it's not enough. `` You really do n't have time to really talk about the most important parts of a daughter-and-mother relationship,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> Decker </PERSON> has been in prison for six years, since her daughter was 11. At first <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> lived with foster parents, then at a children's home. Now she lives alone in the central <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> as she begins her senior year in high school. She cries as she describes life without her mother, whom she calls her best friend. `` You know how you get up for school and your mom always tells you you look nice or you go to prom and they're there,'' she says, haltingly, adding that for her, `` they're not there.'' <PERSON> Luz </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferro </PERSON>, 26, has been in <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> on a drug-dealing conviction for nearly half of her 4-year-old daughter's life. Ms. <PERSON> Ferro </PERSON> says her daughter, <LOCATION> Karina </LOCATION>, who is living with her sister-in-law in <LOCATION> Waukegan </LOCATION>, is too young to fully understand why they have to be separated. `` Today she saw this little tent. She said, `` Oh Mama, this is wonderful,' and I said ` Yes, honey, we're going to be sleeping here tonight.' `` And she said, ` What about tomorrow night?' and I said ` No, you've got to go back home.' `` She said, ` Why Mommy, why do I have to go back? Why ca n't I stay here and we can sleep in the tent?''' That's when Ms. <PERSON> Ferro </PERSON> tried to explain punishment and what it means. `` I tell her ... they punished me because I did something wrong and the punishment is I have to stay away from you,'' she said. `` That's the punishment.''
