ities made no attempt to intervene. Sources said hundreds of people carried away bags of rice from a warehouse in western <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>. In brisk business near the warehouse, they sold the rice to merchants for 100 kyats, or 17 cents per 165-pound bag _ a quarter of the normal price. Nearby, looters took frozen fish, trays and equipment from a <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> warehouse and another group stole provisions and office equipment from a Food and <ORGANIZATION> Beverages </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> warehouse near <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> University. Residents of the <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Okkalapa </LOCATION> earlier reported at least 20 people died in a clash at a biscuit factory between looters and members of a neighborhood committee. The government says the party leadership will meet Monday to consider organizing a referendum on one-party rule. Some diplomats speculate the chaos is being orchestrated to create an excuse for the party to re-establish itself or for military intervention. On Monday, opposition leaders <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> and former Defense Minister Tin Oo threw their support to a demand by one student group that an interim government be formed by Wednesday night or protests will follow Thursday. <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s turmoil mounted after students rioted last September to protest economic policies and then led broader-based street protests in March and June. Street riots flared anew after Ne Win resigned July 23 following 26 years in power and the party chose <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> to succeed him. Government radio said at least 112 people died in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> in rioting against <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON>, who resigned after 17 days in power. Demonstrations have been largely peaceful since <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> took office Aug. 19 as the first civilian leader in 26 years.
