<FIRST>r a PM-SeattleBlackout     09-06 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seattle Blackout,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seattle Blackout Ended, Utility Crews Turn to Preventing
Recurrence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With power restored in a 50-block downtown area after a four-day blackout, crews are checking for wiring similar to the kind that contributed to the city-owned utility's worst outage. The precise cause of the fire that resulted in the outage Wednesday remained undetermined. Power to all but one building in the city's retail, financial and hotel core was restored by Sunday evening. <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> City Light officials attributed the severity of the blackout to the melting of an aluminum, direct-current supply cable for overhead electrical trolley bus lines in an underground vault that also contained six of the utility's 13,000-volt feeder cables. During the height of the blackout, officials estimated that 90 percent of all businesses were closed in the area, which included an estimated 130 restaurants, 55 shops in the popular Pike Place Market, the <LOCATION> Bon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marche </LOCATION> department store, the 875-room Westin Hotel and uncounted other hotels, food stores and taverns. City Light officials said they had no estimate of the utility's losses and the costs of restoring power There was no cost estimate available for losses sustained by the utility's customers. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Forslund </PERSON>, a utility spokesman, said it might be several days before power is restored to the last building without service, a parking garage near the vault, because its low-voltage supply lines were destroyed in the same fire that wrecked the feeder cables. The fire began in low-voltage utility lines between transformers in the vault and individual buildings, said City Light assistant superintendent <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Garman </PERSON>. As the system heated, power to the high-voltage feeder cables should have been cut by `` current limiters,'' but the transit cable melted, and its molten aluminum cut the high-voltage cables before power could be shut off to all but two of them. `` When aluminum melts, it's just like adding gasoline'' to a fire, <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Light </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> McIntosh </PERSON> said. `` It took what would have been a minor inconvenience and turned it into a major event,'' <PERSON> Garman </PERSON> said. `` It's like we had eight or nine welding torches going at the same time.'' City Light crews will check other locations with similar combinations of utility and <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> cables to try to prevent a similar outage, <PERSON> Garman </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
