<HEAD>Japan Launches Experimental Rocket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> today conducted a 62-second test launch of a rocket that is expected to pave the way for lifting larger payloads into space, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said. The 47-foot TR-1 rocket was launched at 8 a.m. from the <ORGANIZATION> Tanegashima </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> Tanegashima </LOCATION> island in southern <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, said agency spokesman <PERSON> Yoshinari </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueda </PERSON>. The rocket dropped into the sea more than a minute after it was launched. He said the two solid rocket boosters attached to the rocket's main body were separated 47.7 seconds after the liftoff. A part of the rocket that collected flight and technical data was recovered by a boat about 60 miles south of <LOCATION> Tanegashima </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ueda </PERSON> said. The TR-1 test rocket was jointly developed by <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Kawasaki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heavy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and cost $ 5.3 million to manufacture and launch, according to <PERSON> Ueda </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s next generation of rockets, the H-2, will be able to carry a 2-ton payload and is to be launched in 1991, <PERSON> Ueda </PERSON> said. Japanese companies now limit rocket payloads to 1,200 pounds. Today's experimental launch is one of three <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> plans to conduct before 1991 to gather further data for the development of the H-2 rocket, <PERSON> Ueda </PERSON> said.
