<SECOND>PM-AIDS Report,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Deleted Criticisms From Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> deleted all criticisms of its efforts to fight AIDS among minorities before making public its report on the subject, The Atlanta Constitution reported today. <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> acknowledged that parts of the analysis were condensed from 16 pages to two pages after they were reviewed by <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> officials, but the newspaper quoted him as refusing to say why the agency deleted critical sections of the report. The newspaper cited government records as its source but did not elaborate. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> has not yet developed an overall strategy to fight AIDS among blacks and Hispanics, who account for more than 40 percent of the victims of the disease. `` If we were to craft a specific, forward-looking game plan, we would involve them in crafting it,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> paid a private consultant $ 12,000 for an analysis of its efforts to fight acquired immune deficiency syndrome among blacks and Hispanics. Among other things, the consultant's report said <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> had no `` cohesive plan of action'' to prevent AIDS among minorities and is unaware of how much of the money given to local health departments for minority AIDS programs actually reached minority populations. The report also said the agency does not have information about the `` knowledge, attitudes and behaviors'' of minority populations. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said the consultant's study was not intended to be used by the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> to provide an overall picture of its efforts to prevent and control AIDS among minorities. He said it was designed to provide him with information to present at a conference of minority health workers and to summarize <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> grants to minority AIDS programs. Surgeon General <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> has said the only way to control AIDS is by educating high-risk segments of the population. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> estimates that among blacks and Hispanics there are 200,000 infected homosexual and bisexual men, 200,000 infected heterosexual drug users, 100,000 infected women and 15,000 infected children and infants.
