 A deputy has been assigned to provide security for the family of <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> for the past five months, a measure defended by the county sheriff as a valid use of tax money. `` I'd say it's public money going to protect a public family,'' <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lankford </PERSON> was quoted as saying in today's editions of The Atlanta Constitution. `` Anything that happened to the King family at this juncture would become international.'' King was assassinated April 4, 1968, in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>. His mother, <PERSON> Alberta </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, was shot to death in 1975 while playing the organ for a Sunday service in an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> church `` It would be an indictment, I think, against our community if another tragedy would befall the family,'' the sheriff said in acknowledging he assigned deputy <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> <PERSON> Willoughby </PERSON> to the post. The newspaper said it learned of the deputy's hiring through county records. County Manager <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Brownlee </PERSON> said the county commission should have been asked to approve the assignment because it amounts to publicly financed protection for a private family. `` That is not something the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commissioners </ORGANIZATION> has authorized,'' he said. `` That's something the sheriff has done.'' <PERSON> Willoughby </PERSON> reports daily to the Martin Luther King Jr.. Center for Non-violent Social Change `` I do n't know if I would say he's a bodyguard, but he's there for the protection of the family as well as for the security of the center itself,'' <PERSON> Lankford </PERSON> said. The civil rights leader's son, <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, said he appreciates the officer's presence. `` I carry the name <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> and that draws crackpots,'' he said. `` A guy came up and approached my mother -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Coretta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- last week,'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said. `` He was just crazy. If he -LRB- <PERSON> Willoughby </PERSON> -RRB- had not been there, something might have happened. Once he saw a police official there, he backed off.''
