<HEAD>Cave Diver Drowns In Panic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIVE OAK, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 21-year-old woman drowned while diving in a water-filled cave when her air tanks ran out after she panicked and swam in the wrong direction, ignoring arrows that pointed the way out, police said. The woman was found Monday in a dead-end corridor in the cave at <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sink </LOCATION>, about 70 feet down and 2,500 feet from the cave's entrance. `` There obviously was some poor judgment and panic,'' said <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Jasper </PERSON>, a member of the team that recovered the body. The woman and her partner, who survived after finding his way out of the cave, had finished a cave-diving course Sunday in the cave that is marked with arrows pointing to the entrance. Deputies said the two had been following a line that marks a course but lost sight of it when they had trouble with one of their flashlights. By the time they got the light back on, they had drifted away from the line, and she apparently panicked and swam away. Her partner lost her. Both divers were trained but had made few dives since finishing their training course, <PERSON> Jasper </PERSON> said.
