<HEAD>Seven Die As `Blinding' Blast Splits Greek Tanker</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with details of blast, suspected cause,
background. ADDS byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HELENA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PERAMA, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A blinding explosion split a Greek oil tanker in two in this port near <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> today, killing at least seven people, authorities said. Seventeen others were injured, many of them with severe burns. Harbormaster <PERSON> Manolis </PERSON> <PERSON> Peloponessios </PERSON> said two bodies had been recovered and at least two workers were missing from the 10:15 a.m. blast that shattered the 86,000-ton Anangel Greatness in this industrial port 10 miles west of the capital. `` We fear they -LRB- the two missing workers -RRB- may be trapped in one of the tanks that's now below water,'' <PERSON> Peloponessios </PERSON> said. Harbor authorities say there was no suspicion of terrorism. Instead, authorities say the blast was believed caused by gas fumes left in the vessel's empty oil tanks. Investigators speculate welders working on the ship during routine maintenance and cleaning may have sparked the blast. Last July 11, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> terrorists launched a grenade and machine gun attack that killed nine people and injured 98 others aboard the City of <LOCATION> Poros </LOCATION> ship as it was returning to <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> from a Greek island cruise. The skipper of the Anangel Greatness, Capt. <PERSON> Anastasios </PERSON> <PERSON> Theocharis </PERSON>, said the ship had been certified free of gas before it sailed into <LOCATION> Perama </LOCATION> on Monday. <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials said the ship carried documents showing all gas had been removed. A Perama police officer who requested anonymity said portions of what appeared to be five other bodies had been found but not yet identified. He said the blast `` produced a blinding light in the sky.'' Officials said the explosion in the vessel's No. 3 fuel tank tore apart the ship as about 25 workers were on board for cleaning and maintenance work. Its 28-member crew also was aboard. `` I was in the control room at the stern when I heard a tremendous noise and everything clattered to the deck,'' <PERSON> Theocharis </PERSON> said. `` People were tossed all over the place. There were body fragments landing on the deck of another tanker berthed next to this one,'' said <PERSON> Costas </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakaros </PERSON>, a metalworkers' union official. <PERSON> Sakaros </PERSON> said crew members on the deck of the adjacent tanker, the 300,000-ton Norwegian flag <PERSON> Ingres </PERSON>, were blown into the air by the force of the blast. The green-and-white vessel started sinking but settled in shallow water, covered in oily scum. Five hours after the blast, black fumes still hung over the waterfront. The explosion also shattered windows in stores and offices around <LOCATION> Perama </LOCATION>.
