<HEAD>Iraq Offers Amnesty for Kurdish Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s ruling <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> today announced a `` general and comprehensive'' amnesty for Kurdish rebels in an apparent effort to counter allegations its forces are using poison gas against the tribesmen. The official <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, reported the council said the rebels, whether in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> or abroad, had 30 days to turn themselves in to be pardoned but would then be allowed to leave the country. Those `` who have obligations abroad, such as jobs or attending school, would be allowed to leave,'' the news agency quoted the announcement as saying. `` Their exit is guaranteed.'' <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>'s move came as Kurdish guerrillas reported fierce fighting in northeast <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> where they said 60,000 troops, with tanks, fighter-bombers and helicopter gunships, were advancing into the rebel strongholds. The rebels are seeking autonomy in their mountainous region, where about 20 million Kurds live in the area where <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> converge. The decree, addressed to `` the glorious <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> nation,'' singled out the Kurds but contained no reference to the Kurds' demand for an autonomous homeland. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s estimated 3.5 million Kurds, about one-fifth of the country's population, have been fighting on and off for 50 years for independence. However, the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> news agency said the amnesty did not extend to `` the traitor,'' <PERSON> Jalal </PERSON> <PERSON> Talabani </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZ