<HEAD>Israeli Troops Isolate Occupied West Bank Town, Set Up Makeshift
Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Israeli troops isolated an occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town today, setting up makeshift army bases, cutting telephone lines and arresting dozens of Palestinians suspected of inciting riots, the army and <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> witnesses said. During today's operation in <LOCATION> Qalqilya </LOCATION>, 55 miles north of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, troops discovered stashes of knives, hatchets, clubs, and underground leaflets outlawed by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> authorities, an army spokesman said. Jewish settlers have claimed Palestinians from <LOCATION> Qalqilya </LOCATION> are key instigators of firebomb and stone-throwing attacks and complained they scattered nails on <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> roads. An army spokesman said troops today imposed a pre-dawn curfew and closed all roads to the town of about 10,000 because the army planned to carry out an `` operation of several stages.'' He declined to elaborate. In all, five <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> towns and refugee camps were under curfew today, confining some 40,000 people to their homes. Arab taxi drivers turned back at army roadblocks reported seeing four helicopters flying overhead and dozens of army vehicles, some pulling mobile homes that were apparently being used as makeshift army bases. They said troops knocked down a wall separating a playground and high school and were pitching tents on the grounds. Police conducted an overnight arrest campaign in <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> east </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, taking 13 Arabs into custody, a spokesman said. Security forces also arrested four <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> Monday night, including two journalists who work for pro-PLO newspapers. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> began the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <OR