<HEAD>High-Rise Sniper Shoots At Cops, Injures 3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sniper fired `` a rain of pellets'' from a high-rise apartment building today, slightly injuring three police officers and closing a busy <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> highway, authorities said. Police said they had pinpointed an 11th-floor apartment as the source of the shots and sent hostage negotiators to talk to a disgruntled tenant, but the man did not respond. Deputy Inspector <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Fogerty </PERSON> said the man apparently had a complaint against the building management. The incident began about 6 a.m. when police responded to reports of shots being fired in the vicinity of the building. The officers stationed themselves along the FDR Drive beside the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> near the <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION>. Police did not describe the type of weapon used, but First Deputy Commissioner <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Condon </PERSON> said `` a rain of pellets'' fell on the officers. Scores of emergency service officers, highway and patrol officers rushed to the scene, cordoning off a four-block area. The busy FDR Drive, a main conduit into <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION>, was closed in both directions in the area. Three pellets superficially wounded three officers. A fourth struck an officer but did not pierce his skin. <PERSON> Fogerty </PERSON> described the man only as being Asian and said he believes he has two children. Police called for an interpreter who speaks Mandarin Chinese. <PERSON> Fogerty </PERSON> said the man refused to open his door, but police could hear voices inside the apartment. Police also tried to call the man but believe his phone may have been disconnected. Officers lowered a video camera from the 12th floor to look into the apartment's windows. Authorities said they could see no people but spotted furniture barricading the front door. <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, who lives on the building's 18th floor, said the man believed to be firig the shots recently moved in and had a reputation for having a bad temper. `` He gets into it with management and the tenants,'' she said.
