<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A prominent black union leader accused of leading an attempted political takeover of a black township took the witness stand Tuesday for the first time in his year-old treason trial. <PERSON> Moses </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayekiso </PERSON>, head of the country's largest metalworkers union, and four co-defendants are charged with seeking to usurp state authority and install their anti-apartheid civic group as an alternative government in <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON>. The 39-year-old activist, whose release has been demanded by many international labor groups, testified about his impoverished childhood and experiences as an illegal migrant worker after he moved to the <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> area in the early 1970s. `` White people lived in civilized places, but next door in <LOCATION> Alexandra </LOCATION>, black people lived in a place where pigs would live,'' said <PERSON> Mayekiso </PERSON>, who will continue his testimony Wednesday. Once a squalid slum wedged amidst white <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> suburbs, <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON> has been upgraded extensively by the government since <PERSON> Mayekiso </PERSON>'s arrest in June 1986. The trial has attracted international attention because of <PERSON> Mayekiso </PERSON>'s position as general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metalworkers </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and because many activists view the prosecution as an attempt to stifle legitimate, peaceful opposition activity. The government alleges that the defendants organized rent and consumer boycotts, sought to undermine the security forces, and established `` people's courts'' in 1985-86, the height of nationwide black unrest. <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON> was one of the most militant black townships at the time, and dozens of people were killed in clashes with security forces. In the past two years, the government has sought to restore control by detaining or restricting leaders of <PERSON> Mayekiso </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Alexandra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> while undertaking a $ 45 million redevlopment program in which sewage, electricity and paved streets are being provided to most of the 100,000 residents. Many of the state witnesses who testified during the early stages of the treason trial were businessmen who said they suffered from boycotts enforced by the action committee. Under cross-examination, some of these witnesses said the local crime rate dropped when young supporters of the action committee began an anti-crime campaign. Another highly publicized court case reaches a critical stage Wednesday when lawyers for the <LOCATION> Sharpeville </LOCATION> Six appear before the Appeal Court to challenge the dismissal of a motion to reopen the murder trial of their black clients. The five men and one woman have been sentenced to hang for their roles in the 1984 mob killing of a black town councilor. There have been an extensive worldwide campaign appealing to President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> to grant clemency. In June, a lower court judge rejected a defense motion to reopen the trial to consider new evidence. At Wednesday's hearing in <LOCATION> Bloemfontein </LOCATION>, the defense lawyers will be asking the <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> _ <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s highest court _ to allow a full appeal of the judge's decision.
