<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dissident groups called Tuesday for the release of about 700 political prisoners before the Olympics and charged the Games were being used to enforce dictatorial rule. The 16 groups issued an appeal to the `` peace lovers'' of the 161 nations taking part in the Olympics to help obtain the release of all political prisoners before the Games begin Sept. 17. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kun-tae </PERSON>, a top dissident, told a news conference attended by 80 other dissidents that the Olympics are being used to cement military rule. He charged the Games will be a mockery if any political prisoners remain behind bars. `` The <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Olympics ... is not an event to pursue global peace but to forcibly reinforce the dictatorship and legitimize violence,'' the groups said in a joint statement. The South Korean government says all political prisoners have been released except for dissidents convicted of violent crimes or communism. Hundreds of political prisoners were freed over the past year. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>, who was released from prison in June, said 370 people are serving sentences for opposing the government and more than 300 others are awaiting trial on political charges. The government says there about 250 dissidents serving criminal sentences or awaiting trial on such charges. The dissidents also denounced communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s exclusion from the Olympics and called for reunification of the divided <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> peninsula. They said the Games were being used to make the division permanent. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has said it will boycott the Olympics because its demand to co-host the Games was turned down. The International Olympic Committee said the Games are awarded to a single city and could not be shared. The dissidents also charged the Olympics were being staged by the government of President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo to enhance its prestige and cement authoritarian rule. `` The dehumanizing torture and terror will not cease and at this very moment, under the euphemism of ` peace during the Olympics,' more people will be arrested,'' the groups said in a statement. They urged other nations to help them fight the government. `` We ask for your full-fledged support in our difficult fight for national sovereignty, democracy and reunification and resistance to <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>'s military dictatorial regime,'' the statement said. The dissidents also demanded withdrawal of the 42,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops based in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> under a mutual defense treaty. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>, a former general who won presidential elections in Decmeber, has introduced broad democratic reforms and dismantled authoritarian controls imposed by former President <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> <PERSON> Doo-hwan </PERSON>. Dissident groups contend the government is a front for continued authoritarian rule by the military and there has been no democratic progress. The dissidents and radical anti-government students have little or no public support and <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>'s popularity has been growing. Most Koreans want the Olympics to be a major success. The Games are seen as a way to propel the nation into the forefront of newly developed nations and continue its rapid industrial development. In another development, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has temporarily halted foreign adoption of its babies to avoid possible controversy during the Olympics. The government has not officially confirmed the ban, but adoption agencies acknowledged they were asked to stop sending babies overseas for adoption for two months before and during the Olympics. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> sends about 7,000 children abroad annually for adoption in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION