<FIRST>u w AM-SchoolComputers     09-06 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Computers,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Students Not Benefitting From Spread of Schoolroom Computers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Computers are moving rapidly into American classrooms, but too many minority and limited-English students are n't reaping the benefits of the new educational technology, an advisory group said in a report released Tuesday. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> schools have acquired nearly 2 million computers during this decade, said the report by the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION>, a non-partisan agency that advises <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on technological matters. Whereas fewer than one school in five had a computer in 1981, now all but 5 percent of schools have at least one, the agency said in a 246-page report titled `` Power On! New Tools For Teaching and Learning.'' `` It has been a very important, useful investment,'' said report director <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>. `` When students are using computers, teachers are trained and the software is appropriate, there really are advances in learning.'' On the downside, the report found that the total number of computers is equal to one for every 30 students; average access is one hour a week, and it would cost $ 4 billion to reduce the student-computer ratio to 3:1. `` In general, classrooms today resemble their ancestors of 50 and 100 years ago much more closely than than they do today's assembly plants, scientific laboratories and operating rooms,'' it said `` Most schools do not have enough computers to make them a central tool of instruction.'' Exacerbating the access problem is the fact that computers tend to be concentrated in affluent schools with smaller student bodies, the report said. The agency report said black students, who generally attend larger schools, have less computer access than white students and `` students with limited English proficiency have the lowest access of all.'' Other problems cited in the report include inadequate teacher training, mediocre educational software and `` the absence of a coordinated federal policy, limited and short-term funding, erratic political support and disorganized research and development efforts across agencies ...'' Only one-third of teachers have even 10 hours of computer training, the agency found, and little of it focused on how to teach with computers. And while there are 10,000 educational software products available, <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION> said, `` their quality could be much better ... Economic risks in the marketplace lead software publishers to play it safe.'' At the current rate of investment, <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said, `` the nation can expect continuing experimentation in some schools, steady but slow improvement in software and spotty access to the technology by students.'' Speeding up the process will require greater efforts by the federal, state and local governments as well as the private sector, she said. On the federal level, <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION> recommended boosting the current $ 240 million investment in learning technology research, including development of software; and encouraging school districts to buy more hardware and software with money from Chapter 1 and Chapter 2, federal programs for disadvantaged students and general education spending by states. The agency's report was requested by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Committee chairman <PERSON> Augustus </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, D-Calif., said in comments accompanying the report that increased federal support for computers in the schools `` would be a good public policy and a wise investment for the future. Rep. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the panel's subcommittee on employment opportunities, said minority and limited-English students must be ensured equal access to `` Access to these technologies is spelled M-O-N-E-Y, but the schools our minority students attend are often overcrowded and underfunded,'' <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> said. `` Technology can narrow or widen these differences. If we do not act ... the classroom of tomorrow may always be left for manana in many of our schools.''
