<HEAD>Others Claim Prize Ticket, But Education is Real Winner, Officials
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The identity of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s $ 55.2 million lottery winner remained a mystery Tuesday, but state officials announced one sure victor: schoolchildren. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> puts 35 percent of lottery sales to education, which now equals $ 350 million in the lottery's first eight months. Officials said the total is twice as much as earlier projections. Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, who opposes the lottery, said Tuesday the state broke $ 1 billion in sales during last week's record number of ticket purchases, which contributed to the world's largest single lottery jackpot. `` This record-breaking pace is exciting, both for the players and public education in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> said. `` While the lottery was never envisioned to meet all the funding needs of education, it's good to know that the games are doing so much to enhance our basic school program.'' Meanwhile, lottery officials say they have heard from several people who claim to have the winning ticket. The six winning numbers were picked in a drawing Saturday night, and lottery officials determined by computer the next day that only one ticket _ purchased by someone in <LOCATION> Longwood </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> _ had the winning combination. A person claiming to represent <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, a school janitor in the Panhandle town of <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION>, called the <ORGANIZATION> Lottery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday and said <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> would come to <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION> Wednesday with the winning ticket, said Lottery Secretary <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>. `` We have no reason to believe that he does or that he does n't until he comes forward with the actual ticket and it goes through our validation process we really do n't know,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Paul </P