<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-SpaceOverview     09-06 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Space Overview,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capsule Landing Problem Reminds Soviets of Danger of Spaceflight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Space, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the first country to put a man in space, has helped make manned space flight routine, giving officials confidence to televise launches and landings live and invite foreigners to climb aboard for a ride. But, like the explosion of the space shuttle Challenger, Tuesday's aborted landing of an Afghan-Soviet space crew again pointed up the dangers of space flight. `` We are already used to everything going smoothly in space,'' commentator <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Tikhomirov </PERSON> told millions of Soviets in a prime time television newscast. `` And some forget about the danger which space research entails. And here, this once more convinces us how complex a matter it is and what a huge amount of abnormal situations awaits cosmonauts in orbit.'' The landing abort threatened to strand two cosmonauts in space with rapidly diminishing supplies of oxygen and food. It came during a busy year in the Soviet manned space program and at a time when the American space shuttle still is grounded because of the Jan. 28, 1986, Challenger disaster, in which all seven crew died. The most enduring symbol of Soviet commitment to manned spaceflight has been the orbiting Mir space station. The research complex, launched in February 1986, is planned as a permanently manned fixture in space. Two cosmonauts have been aboard Mir since last Dec. 21 and plan to break the 326-day space endurance record set by <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Romanenko </PERSON> aboard Mir last year. In June, a Soviet-Bulgarian crew spent 10 days in space, including a visit to Mir. A Soviet-French crew is to blast off Nov. 21 for a monthlong mission. Whether the problems with the Afghan-Soviet mission will delay the Soviet-French flight is not yet clear. Other scheduled flights include a 1990 voyage by an Austrian cosmonaut and a <LOCATION> Malaysian </LOCATION> cosmonaut later. Soviet officials also have indicated they will launch their own space shuttle, unmanned, by year's end. They have emphasized the shuttle will not be flown manned until it is proven safe. The Soviet space program _ long veiled in secrecy since it began with the Oct. 4, 1957, launch of the first satellite, <LOCATION> Sputnik </LOCATION> _ has benefited from <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost, or openness. Since <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Gagarin </PERSON> blasted off as the first man in space in 1961, manned launches have become routine. Soviet officials gained confidence to show launches and in some cases landings on live television and to invite foreigners to watch the blastoffs. The first live TV coverage of a Soviet manned space launch was the Apollo-Soyuz mission in 1975. The first launch to be shown live of an all-Russian crew was in 1984. Space has also served political purposes for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Prior to the Afghan mission, the Soviets had 13 `` guest cosmonauts'' aboard their spacecraft in flights that serve to show off their scientific prowess and promote friendly ties with other countries. Soviets have to think back 17 years to find their last fatal space disaster. Three cosmonauts docked with the Salyut-1 space station, and then during re-entry on June 30, 1971, air leaked out of their capsule and they suffocated. The other casualty of a Soviet space flight was <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Komarov </PERSON>. <PERSON> Komarov </PERSON>'s Soyuz-I capsule crash landed April 24, 1967, but Soviet officials never explained what exactly went wrong. Western space experts believe six to eight other cosmonauts died in training accidents on the ground from 1960-1975.
</TEXT>
