 a fire in parched grass and pine exploded in 24 hours from just 160 acres to more than 25,000 acres Tuesday, sending firefighters fleeing and burning toward some of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state's prime orchards. Fire bosses set up a command post in the tiny <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Entiat </LOCATION>, while helicopters dipped huge buckets into the river and then dumped water on the steep smoldering hillsides above town. The town itself, on the opposite side of the Entiat River from the fire, was in no immediate danger from the flames, which had been blown to within an estimated half a mile of the community of 400 people. The Dinkelman fire's explosive growth overran at least one bulldozer that could not move fast enough and a pickup that broke down, said <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Tasker </PERSON> of the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION>. No serious injuries were reported. `` It's extremely erratic and very, very volatile,'' <PERSON> Tasker </PERSON> said. `` There are gusty winds. It's very dry and very steep. `` I watched it move a half a mile in 10 minutes last night.'' National Guard troops called out by Gov. <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> late Monday were to handle kitchen and camp duties for about 600 firefighters. Intense heat in narrow Mills Canyon caused one home to burst into flames, even though trails had been dug around the home and firefighters had burned away excess vegetation, <PERSON> Tasker </PERSON> said. The fire, reported Sunday afternoon, was reported at just 500 acres as late as 4:30 p.m. Monday. But by 7:30 p.m. it was 3,000 acres, and by 4 a.m. Tuesday it was at least 20,000 acres. The fire was burning on steep hills covered with sage, grass, pine, and some <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> fir, and was beginning to butt up against some orchards in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s premier fruit-growing region. The burned territory was mostly <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> land, but also included state land and <ORGANIZATION> Longview </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fibre </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> property. `` It's an explosive kind of situation,'' DNR spokesman <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> said. `` If you look at the conditions out there, eastern <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is extremely dry. ... The wind is the final ingredient that you need after you get the fire started.''
