<TEXT>
 Police came to Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>'s residence Tuesday and seized a tape of a sermon in which the clergyman defied a government ban and called for an election boycott, <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>'s spokesman said. Meanwhile, the country's largest black-oriented daily newspaper said Tuesday it will no longer carry government advertisements promoting the local elections. The Sowetan, in a notice on its front page, said: `` It has become impossible to justify carrying these advertisements when the community we serve is barred from expressing its sentiments on the elections.'' Many blacks oppose participation in any local or regional elections until the black majority is allowed to vote in national elections. <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, whose sermon Sunday defied the government ban on calls for an election boycott, had offered to provide police with a transcript of his remarks. However, two plainclothes officers came to the Anglican archbishop's official residence outside <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, produced a warrant and demanded a recording which <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>'s press aide, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, had made of the sermon. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, after consulting the church's legal advisers, gave police the tape and a statement confirming the contents of the recording. But <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said he would not be prepared to give evidence if the state tried to call him as a witness against <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, in a telephone interview, said police had called in advance to say they were coming and did not ask to see <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, who was meeting with church members. In his sermon at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION>'s Cathedral in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> deliberately defied state-of-emergency regulations by urging both whites and 