<HEAD>U.N. Chief Asks Major Powers To Accept World Court Jurisdiction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general, asked the permanent <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> members Tuesday to unequivocally accept compulsory jurisdiction of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Of the five, only <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> accepts the court's jurisdiction as compulsory. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> have filed no formal declarations of acceptance, although that does not bar them from appearing before the court. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> severely curtailed its acceptance of court jurisdiction in 1984, just before <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> filed a complaint against the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, accusing it of aiding rebels fighting the <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> government. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said Tuesday, `` Widespread acceptance of the jurisdiction of the court as compulsory would, particularly if taken by the permanent members of the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, put to maximum use the role of the court as a stabilizing factor in international relations.'' The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief spoke at a ceremony celebrating the 75th anniversary of the Peace Palace, of which the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is the major tenant. The court, officially known as the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>, is the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> judicial branch. Dutch Queen <PERSON> Beatrix </PERSON>, Premier <P