<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Dukakis-Bentsen campaign on Tuesday gave a preview of of a television ad touting the Democrats' efforts to win a plant closing notification law. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> campaign director for the presidential ticket of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, said the Democrats' commercial reflects an emphasis on `` the future of the economy in this country. The commercial, which starts airing Wednesday in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, said that <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> `` won the fight'' in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> as sponsor of the law requiring 60 days' notice of a plant closing. A `` fact sheet'' handed out at the screening said <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential nominee <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator, had opposed the plant closing notification bill. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> first vetoed a trade bill that contained the measure, then allowed a separate bill to become law without his signature. The Democrats said Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also opposed the legislation. <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>, a senior adviser to the national <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> presidential campaign and `` Texas-specific'' consultant, said the plant-closing law is `` a phony issue.'' `` Plant closing is a way of them continuing to duck the issues, because they have n't presented anything about the economy that would give people any hope that they could improve on the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> performance or the future <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> performance,'' <PERSON> Black </PERSON> said.
