Cloud, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, 35; <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> joseph </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, 38; <ORGANIZATION> Terre </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Haute </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, 43; <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, 41; <LOCATION> Waterloo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, 35. A frost warning was posted for Wednesday morning for the northern mountains of western <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. Scattered frost also was possible in rural areas of western <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Cool weather continued Tuesday across most of the eastern half of the nation, but warming took place in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and western portions of the northern and central Plains. A few readings were near the 90 degree mark in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. The western third of the nation had mostly 80s, but afternoon temperatures were as low as the 50s and 60s in western <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and along the northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> coast. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55 degrees at <LOCATION> Jamestown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, to 105 degrees at <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The nation's low Tuesday morning was 25 degrees at <LOCATION> Gunnison </LOCATION>, Colo. The forecast for Wednesday called for showers and thunderstorms continuing along and ahead of a stationary front over the <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> coast, southeast <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> peninsula. Windy conditions were expected to spread across the northern Rockies, the northern and central Plains and the upper <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. Most of the nation should have sunny skie