<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Solidarity     09-06 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Solidarity,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Spokesman Rejects Legalizing Solidarity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said Tuesday the promised `` round table'' talks with workers will begin this month but gave no indication it would grant the main demand, legalizing Solidarity. Government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> said supporters of the outlawed free trade union movement should join existing official unions and try to reshape them from within. The official union federation, called OPZZ, said it would oppose allowing new unions into plants where it is established. Solidarity founder <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, who persuaded workers to stop striking in return for the negotiations, declared `` Let them talk,'' but also said such statements `` could destroy the round table.'' An OPZZ resolution said Premier <PERSON> Zbigniew </PERSON> <PERSON> Messner </PERSON>'s government should resign. Its leaders have said government officials should be held personally accountable for economic problems that led to a nationwide wave of strikes last month. Numerous signs in the official press and in speeches at a party conference last month have pointed to changes in the government at the next parliament session, which is expected this month. Such a shakeup would not affect the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership, which holds the real power. Urban said at his first news conference since the strikes ended Saturday that talks with <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and other worker delegates will start this month and include several dozen people. He said the government wants the meetings to begin as soon as possible after preparatory work is finished, but also said they will be canceled automatically if any more `` political'' strikes occur. Talks will cover speeding economic reform, reaching a national consensus for reform, improving living standards and democratizing <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, he said. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> talked supporters into ending the strikes last week after getting a commitment from Interior Minister <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> for negotiations whose topics would include Solidarity. The first independent trade union in the Soviet bloc was born in the labor turmoil of 1980 at the <LOCATION> Lenin </LOCATION> shipyard in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> works as an electrician. Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>'s government imposed martial law in December 1981 to suppress Solidarity and outlawed it the next year Asked about Solidarity's demand for a return to legal status, Urban said that allowing two trade unions in one plant was unacceptable. `` If followers of some tendency connected in the past with Solidarity are a majority in a given plant, then they can either join the -LRB- official -RRB- trade union, outnumbering it and directing it where they wish, or form a coalition, a compromise body'' with the official union. `` The existing legal rules offer a broad scope of possibilities,'' he said, and Solidarity activists made a `` historical mistake'' in boycotting the new government unions created in 1982 after Solidarity was outlawed. Urban said a pro-Solidarity union could be formed in a plant where no union existed, but would not be permitted to use the name Solidarity `` in the present legal situation.'' Reached at home in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> after Urban's news conference, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said: `` Let them talk. But they should remember that they could destroy the round table by such irresponsible statements. This is all I can say.'' Solidarity activists say they want their own union, not membership in the unions established by the government under martial law.
