<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, declaring Republicans have provided good jobs at good wages, was angrily booed and jeered Tuesday by hard-hat shipyard workers chanting, `` Union buster, union buster'' and `` Go home, <PERSON> George </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> encountered the hostile reaction from boilermakers, pipefitters, laborers and electricians during a speech at the Northwest Marine Iron Works. Trying to win votes in a state where he acknowledged he trailed Democratic rival <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` Do not gamble on another liberal Democrat coming out of nowhere.'' He told the crowd of several hundred, `` Do n't listen to all this <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> stuff. They're on the ropes and they've got to make all this noise.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> appeared to have a smattering of support in the audience and was able to win a few cheers when he said he supported the death penalty for drug kingpins and for criminals who kill police officers. The workers also applauded when <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> declared his opposition to furlough programs for prison inmates. However, the audience was largely unfriendly. One prominent sign read, `` Union busting, scab-loving <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>.'' Several people shouted obscenities at <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> during his speech. The vice president said the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration had brought the prime interest rate down from 21 percent and had slashed inflation. He said, `` We're making progress for the working man and women in this country.'' He pledged anew never to raise taxes _ drawing some applause _ and urged the crowd to `` get that same pledge out of the Democrats.'' Opening a two-state swing _ taking him later to <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, another state where <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he was trailing _ he said his goal was to provide a good job at a good wage for everyone who wanted one. `` Good jobs at good wages'' is a main <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign theme. When <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> credited the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration with providing 18 million new jobs over the past six years, the audience booed. `` I know the truth sometimes hurts,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. At times he appeared combative and did not flinch from the heated encounter. When tensions seemed high at one point, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said `` little drama'' and pulled out a 1950 union card showing that he was a dues-paying member of the steelworkers then. `` The Democrats are trying to mislead you, predicting gloom and doom,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` It's quite simple: The other party wo n't get elected unless things get worse, and things are n't going to get worse unless they get elected.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was looking for problems in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s `` new-found American strength. The ice president also said of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, `` It's all a mistake, he'll tell you. Quick, before it's too late, we'd better get serious, he'll tell you, and return to the policies of <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>. `` We just can not go back and lose the progress that we've made in this country.'' After his speech, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> bought a sandwich from a lunch truck and ate it during a meeting with some of the workers. One of them challenged him to explain why his wages have gone from $ 13.36 to $ 9.50 per hour during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. `` You're going through a competitive change,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, referring to the foreign challenge to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> shipyards. Over lunch, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> appeared unperturbed by the crowd's reaction. `` All I need is 51 percent of the vote,'' he said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, en route from a campaign appearance in <LOCATION> Chicago