<HEAD>Reports Stalin Unattended for Hours Before His Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> went unattended by doctors for at least 14 hours after he suffered a fatal stroke in 1953 because his security chief refused to let anyone summon physicians, according to an Estonian newspaper. <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estonia </ORGANIZATION> said in an edition that arrived in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Tuesday that <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s bodyguards found him incapacitated on the floor of his country residence but <PERSON> Lavrenti </PERSON> <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> insisted <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> was sleeping. No one dared contradict <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> was left unattended until the next day, the newspaper reported in its Sunday edition. <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> became head of the secret police in 1938 and carried out bloody purges during the <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> era. The newspaper said its report was based partly on an account recently given to it by a retired security officer, <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rykov </PERSON>, who claimed he was present at <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s dacha, or country home, when <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> died. <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> had ruled since 1924. Little official information was given about his death in March 1953 and his final days have been a mystery to historians. <LOCATION> Sovietskaya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> gave this version: <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> probably died several days before March 5, 1953, the day his death was announced and that given officially as the date of death. <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> died at his dacha and not in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, as official reports said. An autopsy showed <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> suffered a series of small strokes in his final years that affected `` parts of the brain responsible for psychotic activities.'' It took more than six months to embalm and preserve the body before it was put on public display. The newspaper said <PERSON> Rykov </PERSON>, who retired as a major, served as a guard at <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s dacha and recently entered the paper's editorial department and offered to tell his story. `` He could talk for hours about ` the leader of the people,' saving every little fact in his memory,'' the report said. It quoted <PERSON> Rykov </PERSON> was as saying <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> went to bed at 4 a.m. on March 1, 1953, after guests had left. `` In the afternoon guards noticed there was no movement in <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s study or other rooms, but at 6:30 p.m. a light was turned on in the study and in the hall,'' <PERSON> Rykov </PERSON> said, according to the newspaper. It quoted him as saying no one summoned the guards, who became concerned; when one went in to deliver a letter <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> was lying on the carpet in the dining room having `` obvious difficulties in saying anything. Other guards came into the room and carried <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> into the largest hall. It could be seen that he was cold, and he probably was on the floor three to four hours without any help.'' The account said <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> and <PERSON> Georgi </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Malenkov </PERSON>, a close aide who briefly succeeded <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> as top leader, arrived at 3 a.m. on March 2 after <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> telephoned instructions that no one was to say anything about <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s condition. After seeing the unconscious leader, <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> insisted the guards had panicked and that `` <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> was simply sleeping,'' according to the report. Doctors finally were summoned, apparently by <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> who won a power struggle to become <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief later in 1953, and they arrived between 9 a.m. and 10 a.m. `` The doctors were so nervous they could not even take off <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s shirt,'' <PERSON> Rykov </PERSON> was quoted as saying. `` It had to be cut through with scissors. The diagnosis was brain hemorrhage. Treatment was attempted, but it was not surgical. What surgeon could take responsibility for <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s life, especially when <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> frightened everybody, asking whether they could guarantee that <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s life could be preserved?'' <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> was arrested in July 1953 and charged with conspiracy against the state. After a secret trial he and six alleged accomplices where shot in December 1953. The newspaper article described the evening of March 5, 1953, when <PERSON> S.S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Debov </PERSON>, who had embalmed the body of Soviet founder <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>, was summoned. `` One of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s cars took <PERSON> Debov </PERSON> to <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s postmortem examination, which showed some irreversible changes localized in parts of the brain responsible for psychotic activities, which were caused by a number of small hemorrhages,'' <PERSON> Rykov </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s funeral was held on March 9 and the body carried to the tomb. The mausoleum was closed for more than eight months for a more permanent embalming procedure. `` On Nov. 17, 1953, the mausoleum was opened for the people with <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> lying together,'' the newspaper said. It reported the identical coffins remained side by side until 8:25 p.m. on Oct. 31, 1961, when soldiers took <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s remains to a plain gravesite nearby but outside the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> wall. <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> had begun his campaign against what he called the cult of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>.
