<HEAD>Non-Aligned Have Gloomy View of World Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, CYPRUS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign ministers of nations that profess non-alignment welcomed the world's improved political climate, but were less optimistic Tuesday about its economic prospects. `` The international crisis still persists and a number of economic and financial problems remain unresolved with prospects of progress gloomy,'' spokesman <PERSON> Nicos </PERSON> <PERSON> Agathocleous </PERSON> said. A draft statement on the international economy will be presented for approval to the four-day ministers' conference, which President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> will open Wednesday. <PERSON> Agathocleous </PERSON> said the draft statement emphasized that, though there are political developments, particularly between the two superpowers, offering new possibilities of strengthening international cooperation, regrettably the same is not true about the world economic situation.'' A copy obtained by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> deals in detail with 30 issues, ranging from establishment of a new economic order to foreign debt, world hunger, relations between rich and poor nations and global economic cooperation. The draft `` expresses profound concern'' about lack of progress on almost all issues covered. It says problems in the world economy and links between nations make it `` all the more urgent that both the developed and the developing countries engage in construtive dialogue.'' This should be `` aimed at finding common solutions to the problems currently confronting the international economy, including the reform of the international monetary, financial and trading systems in the interest of both the developed and the developing countries,'' the draft declares. Another committee is considering a statement on 39 international political issues, with emphasis on the Palestinian and South African problems. <PERSON> Agathocleous </PERSON> said the 60-page political document, prepared by <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> as the host country, is much shorter than drafts submitted to previous conferences. Delegations from 92 out of non-aligned movement's 101 members are to attend the four-day meting, including 70 foreign ministers. The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, which seeks to turn sympathy for the 9-month-old Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied lands to its political advantage, is expected to win wide support and possibly financial backing. That would give a significant boost to <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s effort to form a provisional government for an independent Palestinian state.
