<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 21st graf pvs, bgng: ``Today I ...'' to
UPDATE with audience reaction, demonstrators.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> accused the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> ticket Tuesday of harboring `` a <ORGANIZATION> Disneyland </ORGANIZATION> defense policy'' that would strip the nation of its military strength and threaten the advances he has made in arms control. Acting as <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s chief surrogate on the campaign trail, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> used some of his harshest rhetoric in weeks to lambast the vice president's opponents in an address to the 70th national convention of the American Legion. The president entered the post-Labor Day election fray during a stop en route to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> following a three-week <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> vacation. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> never mentioned Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> by name, but he made clear he thinks the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor embodies the `` liberal ideology of decline and retreat'' and leads a party that has shown `` remarkable passivity'' and `` unbelievable indecision'' in defense matters while it controlled the White House. In doing so, the president attempted to paint <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as inexperienced in world and military affairs, while hoping to woo into <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s corner those conservative Democrats who twice had voted for his own `` peace through strength'' stand. Using a comic-book analogy to make his point, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> quipped, `` When it comes to defense, the liberal agenda hides behind heroic rhetoric. But this liberal agenda is no Superman; it's no <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Kent </PERSON>; it's <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> trying to impress his date.'' He charged the Democrats with promoting a `` hit list'' of cancellations and delays for the MX missile, the B-1 bomber, the Trident submarine missile and two proposed carrier battle groups for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. `` To that they've added nearly every major new weapons system to become prominent on the scene since the last liberal administration went to its reward, including the Midgetman missile, the Stealth bomber and our Strategic Defense Initiative,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, however, has said he supports the advanced D-5 Trident missile and continued development of the Stealth bomber, so-called because of its ability to escape radar detection. The president accused the Democrats of planning to start `` a unilateral <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> moratorium on underground nuclear testing and a ban on flight testing of missiles.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said that while <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s opponents have praised him for reaching a treaty with the Soviets banning intermediate-range nuclear weapons in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, they also `` opposed deploying the missiles that made that treaty possible ...'' `` They want to conclude more arms reduction treaties, but would cancel or delay the weapons systems on which successful negotiations will depend. ... They profess their devotion to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> but would diminish the role of the very nuclear forces that <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> needs to deter the Soviets. Does that make any sense as military strategy?'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> asked. `` Yes, it comes down to this: After eight hard years of rebuilding <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s strength, do we really want to return to a <LOCATION> Disneyland </LOCATION> defense policy _ with <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Mouse </PERSON> treatment of our men and women in uniform, Goofy strategic plans and <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Duck-like </PERSON> lectures telling us that whatever goes wrong is our own blankety-blank fault?'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> asked. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> contended that even the Soviets might prefer his own approach to that of any Democrat. `` Again and again around the world, our predecessors had shown not the slightest grasp of the fundamentals of strategy and national interest ... And it even came to be said that the Soviets longed for strong, consistent leadership in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, capable of making a deal and sticking to it,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. He derided <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' proposals for boosting conventional forces, which he has dubbed a `` conventional defense initiative,'' in contrast to the president's anti-missile strategic defense program. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> contended a buildup of conventional forces is `` well under way'' and that without the recent achievement of laser-guided munitions, `` we would not have been able to stage our successful strike against -LRB- <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>.'' The president went on to boast how successful his policies have been. `` And our reward is that from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, we are bringing peace to long-raging conflicts, even as we frustrate Soviet aims,'' he contended. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> repeated his oft-used claim that he's `` not given up one square inch of land to communism ... And yet today relations between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are the best they've been in decades. He told his audience, composed of some 7,000 veterans and their families, that he was proud of the military buildup he'd pledged to achieve eight years ago. `` Today I stand before you to report, ` Mission accomplished,''' he said. The Legionnaires interrupted the president frequently with applause. However, on the sidewalk outside the convention hall, about two dozen demonstrators held up signs urging support for the Equal Rights Amendment and opposing the president's policy of aid to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Contra rebels. Before addressing the Legion, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> stopped briefing at <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hastings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, where he participated in dedication ceremonies of a communications arts center. The center is named for the parents of public relations executive <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, a former resident of <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> and long-time <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> acquaintance who had served as the communications director on the the president's 1980 White House campaign.
