<HEAD>Escalating Postal Strike Puts More Than Letters in a Bind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Unemployment checks, last-minute college placements and letters to the editor disappeared into mountains of unsorted mail Tuesday as <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s postal strike escalated. With the nationwide strike in its seventh day, 80 million letters and parcels were held up in darkened post offices. Deliveries in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> were at a virtual halt. All 11,000 mailboxes in the capital were sealed. Private couriers rejoiced, but postal customers scrambled to find alternative ways to deliver their messages, money or bills. The government hired a private courier company to deliver unemployment checks. The Times, <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> and Independent invited readers to send letters to the editor by Fax machine. `` Any system which relies on the post must be in difficulties at a time like this,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Hiscock </PERSON>, head of administration at the <ORGANIZATION> Universities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Admissions. The council, an intermediary between universities and their applicants, set up telephone banks to help match students rejected elsewhere with schools that had openings. <PERSON> Hiscock </PERSON> estimated up to one-third of the annual 15,000 last-minute applications were caught in the backlog. The dispute over regional pay differences and the use of temporary workers shut down 60 of the country's 80 main sorting offices by Tuesday, said <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, a post office spokeswoman. The service has 180,000 workers. Ms. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said that 70,000 workers involved in sorting and delivery stayed away, up from 48,000 Monday. About 15 million letters, compared with a daily 51 million, were being delivered, she said. Earlier estimates said 100 million items were backlogged, but Ms. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> put the figure at 80 mil