<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two cosmonauts returned safely to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> early Wednesday after their descent was aborted twice because of a system malfunction and their food and oxygen began to run out, the official Soviet news agency reported. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported that <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahad </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohmand </PERSON>, the first Afghan in space, and his Soviet crewmate, <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyakhov </PERSON>, touched down at 4:50 a.m. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> time -LRB- 8:50 p.m. EDT Tuesday -RRB- in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. `` Both cosmonauts feel fine after the landing,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The agency said their Soyuz TM-5 space capsule landed 99 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Dzhezkazgan </LOCATION>, a town on the steppes of the republic of <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. The town is about 1,365 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Soviet news reports earlier had said neither cosmonaut was in immediate danger but that the situation soon could become critical. `` Accident! The engine worked 60 seconds and shut off. A violation of the stabilization regime,'' <PERSON> Lyakhov </PERSON> told mission control in an exchange reported by the government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Lyakhov </PERSON>, 47, is a military pilot who has flown in space twice before, and <LOCATION> Mohmand </LOCATION>, 29, is an Afghan air force pilot. <PERSON> Lyakhov </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mohmand </LOCATION> and Soviet doctor <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Polyakov </PERSON> were launched into space Aug. 29 and boarded the orbiting Mir space station two days later. <PERSON> Polyakov </PERSON> remained aboard, but <PERSON> Lyakhov </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Mohmand </LOCATION> undocked the Soyuz at 2:55 a.m. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> time -LRB- 6:55 p.m. Monday EDT -RRB- for the trip home. <PERSON> Polyakov </PERSON> stayed on the Mir to monitor the health of two other cosmonauts who have been in space for more than eight months. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Oberg </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> expert on the Soviet space program who is familiar with the Soyuz TM-5 design, had said Tuesday that time was running out. `` If they can not make the burn tonight to push them back into the atmosphere, they will probably only live another 24 to 48 hours before the carbon dioxide building in the capsule will kill them,'' <PERSON> Oberg </PERSON> said in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> volunteered help but the Soviets declined, saying `` they had a technical problem, but that no assistance was needed.'' The <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> said the Soyuz had split into at least two parts, a normal procedure for re-entry. `` We are tracking two pieces associated with TM-5,'' said Maj. <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondragon </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> NORAD </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. The capsule was in an orbit 226 miles by 206 miles and the ship's living compartment was circling Earth 234 miles at the highest point and 155 miles at the lowest. The Soyuz capsule is designed for trips to and from space, not for long flights. <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> earlier reported that life support systems on the globe-shaped capsule were designed to last two days, meaning that had the cosmonauts not been able to descend, they would have been in jeopardy by Thursday morning. According to the Soviet space official, however, the cosmonauts could have stretched supplies of oxygen, water and food for up to a week. After that the capsule would be like `` a lone boat in the ocean,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity. He did not explain how the air supply could be extended. The capsule would have landed in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> had the descent not been aborted. The space official said contingency landing sites in general were not desirable because no proper ground crews would be there. An <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> article under the headline `` Anxious Hours in Space'' reported this exchange between mission control and the cosmonauts: `` How are things with food?'' a mission controller asked. `` There is no food,'' said <PERSON> Lyakhov </PERSON>. `` But in the accident reserves?'' the controller asked. `` There is some, but why touch it? We will endure,'' <PERSON> Lyakhov </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the cosmonauts `` are in for difficult hours in orbit until the designated time of landing.'' Soviet television showed black-and-white videotape taken from the Soyuz in which the Mir station, whose extended solar panels gave it the shape of a T, grew steadily smaller as the capsule pulled away. Television commentator <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Tikhomirov </PERSON> said later, in a somber voice: `` We are already used to everything going smoothly in space, and some forget about the danger which space research entails. And here this once more convinces us how complex a matter it is and what a huge amount of abnormal situations awaits cosmonauts in orbit.'' Trouble began soon after the Soyuz left its dock on the Mir. An engine used to slow the capsule for entering Earth's atmosphere fired automatically while the vehicle was out of radio contact with ground control, <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said When contact was restored, <PERSON> Lyakhov </PERSON> gave his report that the engine stopped after 60 seconds, far short of the 230 seconds needed to brake the capsule for a safe re-entry, Soviet media said. Controllers decided to delay another attempt for three hours, <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> reported. During that time, scientists found that sunlight had interfered with a sensor in an infrared guidance system and a computer automatically terminated the engine burn. Seven minutes later, the sensor locked onto its correct target and the guidance system worked properly. The engine fired again, but because the on-board computer had not been reprogrammed the capsule was sent on a trajectory for a landing in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the reports said. The cosmonauts stopped the engine manually after three seconds and tried again, but that time the engine stopped after six seconds and the decision was made to wait until Wednesday. <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryumin </PERSON>, a cosmonaut and the mission chief, told <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>: `` Do n't worry, nothing terrible has happened yet. The life support system will last for two days.''
