<HEAD>Opposition Given Access to National Television</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opponents of the military government have been given limited access to national television for the first time in 15 years as both sides formally opened their campaigns for the presidential plebiscite. Under a new electoral law that went into effect late Monday, supporters of President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> and the opposition will have 15 minutes of free time daily on national television to carry their messages to <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s 7.2 million registered voters. Neither side has to pay for the programs that by law can continue until Oct. 1, four days before the plebiscite in which Gen. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, the army commander, is the only candidate. The opposition, which has complained about its lack of access to government-controlled television, criticized the late hour set by the new law. It states both sides will have 15 minutes alternating between the time period of 10:45 p.m. and 11: .15 p.m. `` For the first time in 15 years those who do not share the government views have the opportunity to adress you on television,'' said <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Banados </PERSON>, the opposition's official announcer in opening the Monday night program. `` Fifteen minutes in 15 years is not too much.'' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> led the coup in September 1973 that ousted the elected government of Marxist President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> has ruled the country since then and was selected last month by the military junta he controls as the sole candidate in next month's ballot In the referendum Chileans will vote `` yes'' or `` no'' on <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>. If he is approved he will start an eight-year term as president next March. If rejected, a multiple-candidate election will take place in December 1989 with <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> remaining in power until then. During the opposition's television program Monday its campaign song, `` <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> is Coming,'' was played constantly. The program ended with <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>, a centrist who is the main spokesman for a 16-group coalition, urging a `` no'' vote in the plebiscite and challenging <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> to a a face-to-face debate on national television. The government based its program mainly on economics, saying inflation had been reduced to an annual rate of about 10 percent and noting the increase in exports. It also showed television clips and photographs of the street violence, food shortages and other economic problems during <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>'s government. An announcer said those conditions would return if the referendum is defeated. The 15-minute programs will be the only television advertising allowed to the opposition. Paid political advertising is banned by law on the television stations that are operated either by the government or various universities. The government has broadcast a series of referendum-related advertisements but officials claimed they did not violate the law and were a `` legitimate promotion of the government's work and achievements.''
