<HEAD>Pope's Visit to Marxist Mozambique Comes amid Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, note pope visits Sept. 16-19</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>'s customary message of peace and reconciliation could be a controversial one when he visits <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, a southern African nation wracked by 12 years of civil war, drought and systematic destruction of public facilities. A newsletter issued last year by <ORGANIZATION> Frelimo </ORGANIZATION>, the governing Marxist party, called the former <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> colony's <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> bishops `` enemies of the people'' after they suggested the government meet with guerrillas of the Mozambican National Resistance. But Cardinal <PERSON> Alexandre </PERSON> <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> says he hopes the pope will call for reconciliation when he visits the country Sept. 16-19. President <PERSON> Joaquim </PERSON> <PERSON> Chissano </PERSON>, who was visiting the pope in the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> when the bishops made their plea, said it was impossible to negotiate with the guerrillas who, he charged, mutilate children, burn schools and hospitals, and massacre villagers. The guerrilla movement, known as <ORGANIZATION> RENAMO </ORGANIZATION>, denies such charges and says it is fighting to replace the Marxist government with a democratic one. `` We hope -LRB- the pope -RRB- will say something about peace since we are in this situation of war,'' said <PERSON> Dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>, who became a cardinal in June. `` We do n't see how we can end this struggle without reconciliation. ... It is necessary to have dialogue with these people.'' Foreign Minister <PERSON> Pascoal </PERSON> <PERSON> Mocumbi </PERSON> said the government hopes the pope will not appeal for negotiations with <ORGANIZATION> RENAMO </ORGANIZATION>. He said no one had the right to suggest that the government `` should talk with terrorists, with those who commit massacres, ... those who have been roundly condemned, not only by <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> but by the international community.'' Job Chambal, director of the government's <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Religious </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, is overseeing the return of some church property confiscated when <ORGANIZATION> Frelimo </ORGANIZATION> came to power at independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in 1975. He said of the bishops: `` Our quarrel with them is not the fact that they called for negotiations _ any <LOCATION> Mozambican </LOCATION> is free to think that. The one thing that worried the government was to ... say that the government as well as <ORGANIZATION> RENAMO </ORGANIZATION> are responsible for the war.'' <PERSON> Chambal </PERSON> said the plan to return all confiscated church property used for worship came coincidentally three months before the pope's visit `` We were not trying to please the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>,'' he said. `` It's a way of showing we do n't belong to an evil empire.'' Since 1982, when the late President <PERSON> Samora </PERSON> <PERSON> Machel </PERSON> held meetings with church leaders, the government has sought to ease tension between the churches and <ORGANIZATION> Frelimo </ORGANIZATION>. The government invited the pope to visit <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> in his capacity as head of the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> state, and it is sharing expenses with the local church. `` It's very expensive, but it's very important,'' Chambal said. `` The willingness of the pope to come to <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> means there's been a very big improvement because people have understood what it means when we say we have a socialist state. `` We are Marxists, but all of us in government have some religious background,'' said <PERSON> Chambal </PERSON>, who was reared a Presbyterian. `` We still have some religious feeling. Even our revolutionary songs have a religious taste. But our children will be more Marxist, and teach their children to be Marxists.'' He said the government wants children to be influenced only by the state until they are 18, when they can choose whether to go to church, but this policy is not enforced. In the years immediately after independence, some churches were closed, services were interrupted and religious activity was officially discouraged. Now churches operate freely. Both cathedral services and prayer meetings in the <PERSON> bush </PERSON> are packed on Sundays. The Frelimo revolutionaries accused Roman Catholic bishops and priests of cooperating with the Portuguese colonial government and opposing independence in return for a favored position as a state church. The cardinal says some Portuguese clergymen supported colonialism, but denies the <ORGANIZATION> Mozambican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> as a whole was against independence. All church-state problems are not resolved, Cardinal <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> said, but he maintained the government does not understand the church's goals. `` They suppose we want only to teach those who want to be religious leaders,'' he said. `` We also want to prepare the people for running the country.'' <PERSON> Dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> said that of <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>'s 14.5 million people, 2 million are Catholics.
</TEXT>
