<HEAD>Jetliner Crash Heats up Debate on Hong Kong's Airport</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The fatal crash landing of a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> jetliner has fired up debate on replacing <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s airport, known for its harrowing flight path that skims the rooftops of crowded <LOCATION> Kowloon </LOCATION> peninsula. The British-built Trident jetliner skidded off <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>'s sole runway into the sea in a torrential downpour Aug. 31, killing seven people in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s worst air accident in 21 years. The accident came at a time when the British colony is considering construction of a new airport away from congested urban areas. The government is funding three surveys to evaluate various proposals. The colony's governor, Sir <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, said immediately following the crash that it should have no bearing on the future of the existing airport, which is known as Kai Tak. The English-language <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> newspaper agreed, but noted in an editorial that `` there is no doubt that the crash will focus renewed attention on the apparently never-ending saga of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s need for expanded aviation facilities.'' <PERSON> Kai </PERSON> <PERSON> Tak </PERSON> is squeezed between the sea and the impossibly crowded neighborhoods of <LOCATION> Kowloon </LOCATION>, one of the colony's major urban areas. The runway juts into <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s famed harbor and is surrounded on three sides by water. Use of the airport has expanded rapidly. Last year, 12.7 million passengers were handled, an increase of 20 percent from the year before and nearly 50 percent from 1982. Movement of aircraft reached 73,370 planes in 1986, an increase of 13.2 percent from the previous year. `` The single runway, required to handle an aircraft every 180 seconds during peak hours, has exhausted its possibilities,'' the Morning Post said. The government says the runway can handle up to 30 planes an hour. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Sit </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kong </ORGANIZATION> professor who studies urban problems, expressed concern that the airport's enviable safety record may run into trouble as traffic increases. `` We've been lucky,'' he said. `` So far, the accidents all happened on the harbor side of the airport, not on the landward side.'' Although the Chinese jetliner crashed while approaching the runway from the harbor, flights typically make their final approach over <LOCATION> Kowloon </LOCATION>. `` The approach of the airport obviously requires very careful maneuvering by the pilots concerned and very precise control ... by the airport,'' Sit said. Passengers rarely forget the final moments before touchdown when planes come breathtakingly close to <LOCATION> Kowloon </LOCATION>'s buildings <PERSON> Kai </PERSON> <PERSON> Tak </PERSON> critics note the airport becomes paralyzed whenever the runway is disrupted, cutting the colony's main transportation link to the outside world. The Chinese jetliner crash stopped traffic for about six hours. They also argue that the airport's urban location makes life miserable for many local residents. A recent study estimated 1 million people suffer unacceptable noise from <PERSON> Kai </PERSON> <PERSON> Tak </PERSON>. Government officials have been considering replacement possibilities for years and are actively looking at two sites near outlying <LOCATION> Lantau </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> for a new airport. A final decision has been promised by the end of 1989. The most ambitious proposal is from a group led by <ORGANIZATION> Hopewell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd </ORGANIZATION>. The massive $ 3.08 billion-plan would include an airport, seaport, road and railway complex on reclaimed land off the island's east coast near <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> island. The tiny <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> territory of <LOCATION> Macao </LOCATION>, 40 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, also has proposed building its own international airport. And <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which regains sovereignty over <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> in 1997, plans to construct an airport in its <LOCATION> Shenzhen </LOCATION> special economic zone just over the <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> border. Sit said that airport would only `` help to ease our trouble a little bit.'' He believes <PERSON> Kai </PERSON> <PERSON> Tak </PERSON> will reach capacity in three to five years, around the time construction could be starting on a new airport, unless the government bows to pressure to act faster. `` That would mean they only start construction when the airport itself has exceeded capacity,'' Sit said. `` It would be fairly difficult for <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> to operate as an international financial trading and tourist center, unless we have some other arrangement.'
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs Sept. 13</NOTE>
