 Today is Sunday, Sept. 11, the 255th day of 1988. There are 111 days left in the year. The Jewish New Year, <LOCATION> Rosh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hashanah </LOCATION>, begins at sunset. Today's highlight in history: On Sept. 11, 1777, during the American Revolution, forces under Gen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> suffered defeat at the hands of the British in the Battle of <ORGANIZATION> Brandywine </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, Del. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s troops were forced back into <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, which fell to the British On this date: In 1789, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> was appointed secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>. In 1814, an American fleet scored a decisive victory over the British in the Battle of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Champlain </LOCATION> in the War of 1812. In 1850, the `` Swedish Nightingale'' _ <PERSON> Jenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Lind </PERSON> _ gave her first concert in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, at Castle Garden in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In 1885, author <PERSON> D.H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Eastwood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. In 1936, President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> dedicated <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dam </LOCATION> _ now known as <ORGANIZATION> Hoover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dam </ORGANIZATION> _ by pressing a key in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to signal the startup of the dam's first hydroelectric generator in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>. In 1941, in <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, aviation hero <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindbergh </PERSON> charged `` the British, the Jewish and the Roosevelt administration'' were trying to involve the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in World War II. In 1944, President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> and <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> met in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> at the second Quebec Conference. In 1971, former Soviet leader <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> died of a heart attack at the age of 77. In 1973, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s President, <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, died in a violent military coup that overthrew his government. In 1982, 46 people were killed in a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> helicopter crash near <LOCATION> Mannheim </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. In 1985, <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION> cracked career hit number 4,192 off <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Show </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Padres </ORGANIZATION>, eclipsing the record held by <PERSON> Ty </PERSON> <PERSON> Cobb </PERSON>. Ten years ago: <PERSON> Georgi </PERSON> <PERSON> Markov </PERSON>, a Bulgarian defector, died at a <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> hospital four days after he was stabbed by a man wielding a poisoned umbrella tip. -LRB- Bulgarian authorities have denied their agents killed <PERSON> Markov </PERSON>. -RRB- Five years ago: The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> issued a revised transcript of the monitored remarks of the Soviet pilot who shot down a Korean jetliner Sept. 1. The transcript quoted the pilot as saying he had fired `` cannon burst'' before shooting down the plane with 269 people aboard. One year ago: CBS anchorman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rather </PERSON>, angered because coverage of a tennis tournament had delayed the start of his 6:30 p.m. newscast, walked off the set of `` The CBS Evening News,'' leaving the network `` black'' for six minutes when the sports coverage abruptly ended. Today's Birthdays: Former <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> is 71. Football coach <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Landry </PERSON> is 64. Actor <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Holliman </PERSON> is 60. Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, R-Ore. is 56 Movie director <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> -LRB- `` The Untouchables'' -RRB- is 48. Thought for Today: `` A bad cause requires many words.'' _ German proverb.
