<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv07   09-06 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 07 ,0712</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Wednesday, Sept. 7</NOTE>
<HEAD>To The Government: Butt Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As an authority on economic and business productivity, <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> <PERSON> Grayson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> watches in amazement as one legislator after another thinks government has the answers. Having served in three administrations, <PERSON> Grayson </PERSON> knows how limited are government's abilities to intervene in the marketplace and correct its problems, specifically when they involve global competitiveness. In that area, he says, there are important things that government should not do, no matter how insistent and intense the pressure. In keeping with that belief, he and associate <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Dell </PERSON> have issued some cautionary advice. Their views are in the form of a book titled, `` American Business: A Two-Minute Warning,'' although it would take even the most efficient and productive reader a lot longer than that to digest their advice. <PERSON> Grayson </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Productivity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, is well-grounded in his subject, having been President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s price commissioner, and a member of President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s Commission on the Agenda for the 80s and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Productivity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> From such vantage points, says <PERSON> Grayson </PERSON>, he has observed growing pressure on government to `` do something'' about <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s competitive posture, which is reflected in the balance of payments deficit and other problems Over the past five years, he says, there have been 112 recommendations for government action by 21 councils, commissions, congressional hearings and study groups on productivity and competitiveness. It is frightening, say <PERSON> Grayson </PERSON> and <PERSON> O'Dell </PERSON>, that the 99th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had 108 committees and subcommittees in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and 178 in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, with 3,000 staffers `` feeling they must do something to help American competitiveness.'' Stating that such determination by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to do something `` keeps us awake at night,'' the authors name five things they feel government must not do to `` help American competitiveness.'' 1. The single worst thing is to increase protection, say <PERSON> Grayson </PERSON> and <PERSON> O'Dell </PERSON>. They say it invites reciprocity, lowers efficiency and shrinks export-related jobs. Granting protection, they say, `` is like putting an industry on a life-support system. It may prolong life for a while, but it ca n't restore health.'' 2. Government should not establish industrial policies. Industrial policies are, in effect, attempts at centrally directing the economy to specific national goals. Call it `` national planning'' and you might get an argument, but you would also have material to defend yourself. Industrial policies have been resurrected under the labels of `` trade policies'' or `` competitiveness policies'' or `` living standards acts.'' <PERSON> Grayson </PERSON> and <PERSON> O'Dell </PERSON> maintain that government personnel are not, by instinct or background, entrepreneurs or managers, and that their allocation decisions would be worse than those of the private sector. Furthermore, they observe, authors and administrators of policies and laws tend to be lawyers or economists with little knowledge of business operations. And, they ask, are n't we aware that government can not plan long range and can not stay atop the rapid, continuous adjustments of a dynamic market? 3. The country should avoid currency devaluation as a competitiveness strategy. Among other things, they argue, devaluing the dollar makes the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> compete on the basis of a lower standard of living. `` Devaluation keeps knocking the dollar down until American wages are cheap enough to compete.'' 4. Capital investment should n't be overemphasized. `` We stress that capital investment is not only important for productivity improvement, it is essential,'' they say. `` What we argue against is the overemphasis and wrong emphasis on capital investment.'' One of their reasons for so thinking is that `` merely calling for more capital investment confuses the volume of capital investment with the productivity of that investment.'' 5. More research and development is not necessarily better. `` The biggest competitive problem is not the amount spent on R & amp; D, but on what is spent, and what is done with the ideas and techniques after discovery.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, they point out, is still the world leader in originating new ideas. But, `` while that is great for the good of the world, what counts in competitiveness is rapid commercialization of new knowledge.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday, Sept. 7.</NOTE>
