<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Sept. 12, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Willem Dafoe Talks About ``That Movie''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Willem </PERSON> <PERSON> Dafoe </PERSON> is a modest man, but he could n't help thinking the time was right to play the title role in `` The Last Temptation of Christ. `` It made all the sense in the world,'' he said. `` I thought, ` Yes, of course. Perfect. It's a good role. I feel right for it right now.' I'm just at the point in my life where I'm concerned with some of the things he's speaking about. The struggle between the body and the spirit is something I'm interested in.'' Few films have generated as much controversy as <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON>'s `` The Last Temptation of Christ.'' Based on the novel by <PERSON> Nikos </PERSON> <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON>, it depicts an angst-ridden <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>, torn between desires of the mind and body. In a dream sequence, he is spared the cross, sleeps with <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Magdalene </PERSON> and has children. The movie has drawn fierce protests from some religious groups. `` I was a little surprised,'' <PERSON> Dafoe </PERSON> said. `` I knew there was some resistance. ... I never thought it would be to this extent and take this kind of shape.'' However, the publicity generated from the protests has helped the movie at the box office. `` It's always a terrific thing for a publicity campaign,'' <PERSON> Dafoe </PERSON> said. `` But it colors everything in a negative light. Maybe that's a trade-off to the publicity. <PERSON> Dafoe </PERSON> was eager to work with <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON>, the director of `` Mean Streets,'' `` Taxi Driver'' and `` Raging Bull.'' `` He just gave me a certain kind of confidence and authority. He kept me on the track. He makes you feel comfortable; he gives you that room. You feel totally unencumbered, free, yet you feel a guiding hand.'' <PERSON> Dafoe </PERSON> also enjoyed working with the cast, which included <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Hershey </PERSON> as <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Magdalene </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowie </PERSON> as <PERSON> Pontius </PERSON> <PERSON> Pilate </PERSON>. `` There was a real sense of purpose,'' he said. `` Marty commands a lot of respect. There was very little money, and the actors were doing it for scale. Everyone wanted to be there. A real ensemble feel.'' Although <PERSON> Dafoe </PERSON> had seen other biblical movies, he had no interest in repeating others' performances. `` I really did n't concern myself with what kind of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> I was going to be _ the responsibility of playing that role, all the associations, all the information. I thought I would find a place to scrub myself clean of all that and really start out from a wonderfully innocent place.'' <PERSON> Dafoe </PERSON>'s confidence was helped by his faith in Scorsese: `` I would not be cowed by the role. It was a very risky thing. If you're going to be in a situation like that, you might as well be with <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON>.'' The intensity of his performance in `` Last Temptation'' can be measured by his eyes, which rarely blink on camera. `` No matter what you do, it has mythic proportions,'' he said. `` When you're speaking, no matter the context, there is some kind of concentration that's not of this world. `` The general tendency is to look as deeply as you can into the back of someone's brain and deeply understand with every cell in your body what you're saying.'' The 33-year-old actor talked about his career at the Performing Garage, home of the <ORGANIZATION> Wooster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, an experimental theater company. <PERSON> Dafoe </PERSON> is a member and does business there. He was born July 22, 1955, in <LOCATION> Appleton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, and was early attracted to the stage. `` Simply moronic reasons,'' he said, smiling. `` It's fun, it's enjoyable. I like pretending.'' As he grew older, his feelings for acting deepened. `` In the end, it's for its own sake _ for beauty's sake. A lot of professions, you're tracked. You do this, you get that. In acting, you become the canvas. It totally goes back to you,'' he said. `` You're constantly questioning why you do what you do. You're constantly evolving It's a healthy way to live, but very difficult.'' He became a full-time actor at 18, and in 1977, he saw the Wooster Group give a performance of `` Rumstick Road.'' `` It was just unlike anything I'd ever seen,'' he said. `` The event was so extraordinary. It touched my heart. There's no accounting for it. I could n't identify it. It had that kind of maniac energy and this really fluid transformation.'' <PERSON> Dafoe </PERSON> joined the <ORGANIZATION> Wooster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> but also pursued a career in film. After appearing in a few minor films in 1983, he began to attract attention with `` Streets of Fire'' in 1984 and `` To Live and Die in <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION>'' in 1985. His big breakthrough came the following year with `` Platoon,'' <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON>'s Academy Award-winning film about the Vietnam War. <PERSON> Dafoe </PERSON>'s portrayal of the sympathetic Sergeant <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> earned him an Oscar nomination for supporting actor. Despite film work, he has continued his involvement with the <ORGANIZATION> Wooster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. `` The whole desire to play around with forms is a liberating thing for an actor,'' he said.
</TEXT>
