<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 18</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&amp;w
photos.)</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Republican presidential nominee <PERSON> George </PERSON> `` Poppy'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> went off to <ORGANIZATION> Phillips </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Andover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, at age 13, before the word `` preppy'' had been invented, and later attended <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>. A reporter looking into the school days of both <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his Democratic opponent, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, talked with former classmates and teachers who generally remember him as `` a real nice guy'' and a good athlete. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' schoolmates will get their say in the next story.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By HUGH A. MULLIGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANDOVER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has shed the <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> glasses, dropped his twangy voice a note or two and now eschews button-down shirts _ anything to get rid of the preppy image that dogs his run for president against <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> `` There's a tendency to have you fit into a mold,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> vice president complained recently. `` The mold for me is a kind of <ORGANIZATION> Ivy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> elitist, and I resist it.'' Alas, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> might have avoided the whole Eastern establishment WASP wimp caricature had he been born in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, like his father, or in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> like his mother's clan or in <LOCATION> Kingsport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, like older brother <PERSON> Prescott </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. Well, almost <PERSON> Prescott </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON> did go to <LOCATION> Yale </LOCATION>, as did <PERSON> George </PERSON>, his three brothers, four uncles and cousins by the half-dozens. Still, <PERSON> Dad </PERSON> was a <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> hardware salesman before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rubber absorbed his small firm and transferred him to <LOCATION> Braintree </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> George </PERSON> was born on June 12, 1924, in nearby <PERSON> Milton </PERSON>. A transfer to the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office relocated the family in the affluent commuter town of <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, but they were n't established Easterners until Dad turned to investment banking, bought that 11-room Victorian house with a huge rolling lawn on <PERSON> Grove </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> and became moderator of the town meeting Later, years later, when <PERSON> George </PERSON> was out of <LOCATION> Yale </LOCATION> and wildcatting for oil in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, his father twice won election to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and became a golfing partner of <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>. <PERSON> George </PERSON> at age 5 went off to the <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION> Country Day School. From the start, he was a good athlete, thanks to Mom, <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who had made it to the finals of the Girls National Tennis Championship and is still going strong, riding her bike at 86, handing out campaign literature. `` Physically, she is a small woman, but she is made of mighty stuff,'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> wrote in a Mother's Day salute three years ago for the <ORGANIZATION> Greenwich </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. `` Nine months into her first pregnancy she played baseball. Her last time up she hit a home run and without missing a base continued right off the field to the hospital to deliver Pres.'' Sundays after Episcopal services at <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, there was always a baseball game on the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> lawn with <PERSON> George </PERSON>, being left-handed, holding down first base, a position he excelled at when he captained the <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> nine into the national collegiate finals and got to meet Babe <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON>. `` Poppy, as we called him, had good hand-to-eye coordination,'' recalls retired <ORGANIZATION> Time-Life </ORGANIZATION> executive <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingels </PERSON>, a classmate at the Country Day School. `` He was a running back on our football team, good also at soccer, tennis and wrestling. We were both a year younger than the others and rivals for head of the class.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> was nicknamed `` Little Pop,'' then `` Poppy,'' for his hero worship of his maternal grandfather, <PERSON> George </PERSON> `` Pop'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, a fine athlete who donated the Walker Cup to golf. Grandpa <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, who presided over those blissful summers in the rambling ocean-front house at <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> now owns, was `` a staunch Democrat'' until <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> came along. `` <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> made him see red,'' a friend recalls. <PERSON> Ingels </PERSON> remembers `` staying over'' at the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> home on Halloween and hiding out in the graveyard after `` squirting people with a water pistol loaded with green ink and belting them with a sock full of flour.'' `` Poppy _ I never knew him as anything else _ was a real nice guy, decent and honest, never a braggart. Maybe that's the trouble with the world today. Suddenly a nice guy is a wimp. He was never a wimp in my book. He's not the type to shake his fist at people, but he's got plenty of strong fibers.'' One day fifth-grade teacher <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> got them thinking about the future: `` Some of you will go into business and be leaders. Others may go into politics. Who knows, one of you might be president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' He had no one in mind then, but at 89 he remembers <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as `` a good athlete. He and his brothers always had a real code of ethics.'' Breakfast in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> household began with mother or father reading a passage from the Bible. Both parents stressed values, especially fairness, modesty and service to others, and were pleased with <PERSON> George </PERSON>'s report card evaluation: `` Claims no more than his fair share of attention.''
</TEXT>
