<TEXT>
 On a recent visit to his alma mater, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> remembered Pearl Harbor Day, 1941, `` slouching across campus with my roommate. We kept it on our minds that the Germans were invading <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. We knew exactly what we had to do. We had to beat <LOCATION> Exeter </LOCATION> at football.'' Which they did, 14-13, with the whole school singing and shouting through the snowy night on that special train back from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>. War was almost a curriculum elective by then. The boys sold war bonds, donated their downtown treats money to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.O. </ORGANIZATION>, gathered up magazines in the dorms every Thursday for the soldiers at nearby <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Devens </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Pot </PERSON> <PERSON> Pourri </PERSON> lost its slick cover to the wartime paper shortage. The class historian noted that `` the whole school thrilled to an address at morning chapel by Col. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stimson </PERSON>, the Secretary of War'' and an <LOCATION> Andover </LOCATION> trustee. <PERSON> George </PERSON>, as chairman of the student deacons, got to escort the secretary to the podium, in addition to his regular duties of checking attendance and taking up the collection. Caught up in the patriotic fervor, <PERSON> George </PERSON> on his 18th birthday, just a few days after graduation, took the train to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> to enlist in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. In the yearbook poll of 193 graduates, he ranked third behind varsity quarterback <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Vose </PERSON> as `` most popular,'' `` handsomest'' `` most respected'' and `` best all-around fellow.'' He rated second in `` most faculty drag'' and was out of the running as `` most intelligent,'' `` most likely to succeed'' and `` ladies' man.'' His name was read out in chapel on a September morning in 1944 when his carrier-based torpedo bomber was reported shot down in flames in a raid on the Japanese airstrips on <LOCATION> Chichi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jima </LOCATION> and again when word came that he had been plucked from a rubber raft in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> by a surfacing submarine, the USS Finback. For <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the preppy years were essentially over. When he entered <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> in November l945, he was hardly your <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Arno </PERSON> cartoon caricature of a Yalie, although typical of that first postwar term when three out of five were veterans and gray flannels were beginning to replace officer pink on the old campus. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was already married and soon to start a family. He and <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> first lived in a Quonset hut near the <PERSON> Payne </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON> gym, then in a series of apartments, the last one, as he ad-libbed after a recent campus speech, so close to President <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON>'s house `` you could look in the window and see his wife taking a bath. Poppy, as he was still called, sailed though an accelerated economics program in 2 -LCB- years, won the <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> <PERSON> Prize </PERSON> as the outstanding junior and went on to earn Phi Beta Kappa. He also found time to burp baby <PERSON> George </PERSON>, play three years of varsity baseball, letter in soccer and take part in an occcasional fraternity beer bust at the <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kappa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Epsilon </ORGANIZATION> house. His name did n't make the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION> police blotter for that riot after the pep rally on the eve of the <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> football game. His l948 classbook supplied some vivid details: `` Just how many heads collided with billy sticks can not accurately be counted nor how many rolls of toilet paper flew out of dormitory windows, but there is someone who claims he personally stopped 31 trolley cars.'' Like his father before him, and such diverse luminaries as <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Taft </PERSON>, <PERSON> Averell </PERSON> <PERSON> Harriman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Luce </PERSON>, <PERSON> Archibald </PERSON> <PERSON> MacLeish </PERSON>, <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sloane </PERSON> <PERSON> Coffin </PERSON>, <PERSON> George </PERSON> was one of l5 juniors tapped for Skull and Bones, the oldest and most secret of the societies anchoring <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>'s old boy network. He went through the rumored -LRB- Bonesmen never tell -RRB- initiation of climbing into a coffin to confess his sins -LRB- preferably erotic -RRB- in `` The Tomb,'' the windowless, brown sandstone club house. Although <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> went 3 for 5, the big disappointment in his senior year was the baseball team's loss to the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> in the national collegiate finals. As one who knew him well in the preppy days, has kept in touch since the college years and `` will be rooting for him in the <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>,'' old coach <PERSON> Deke </PERSON> <PERSON> DiClementi </PERSON> has a word of caution for reporters on the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> beat: `` Do n't say he's a nice guy. He really IS a nice guy. That's what's killing him.
