<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 18</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Julie </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, who has spent much of the last seven years in television, has come home to the theater and a yearlong tour in `` Driving Miss Daisy.'' Not that she had deserted the stage completely while toiling on the CBS nighttime soap opera `` Knots Landing.'' Between seasons as the vulnerable, often silly and very southern Lilimae Clements on television, Miss <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> found time for short theater engagements, particularly in her one-woman shows based on the lives of <PERSON> Emily </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Charlotte </PERSON> <PERSON> Bronte </PERSON>. But `` Knots Landing'' occupied most of her career until she was written out of the show last fall. When last seen on the program, she and Red Buttons were riding off into the sunset in a motor home. Now the actress is on the road for real, this time in a tour that began in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> after Labor Day and will end next summer in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. Why submit to the rigors of touring? `` It's a perfect play,'' Miss <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> says in describing `` Driving Miss Daisy,'' which chronicles the 25-year relationship between an elderly <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> widow and her black chauffeur. `` There's an absolute truth about it,'' she adds. `` It's well-conceived and well-constructed It's like when you look in one of those small boxes and there are colors changing all the time. That's the way working on something like this is. It's never-ending: The little feelings that eddy out from all the scenes go into the next scene. The play, still running off-Broadway at the <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Houseman </PERSON> <PERSON> Theater </PERSON>, was a first effort by <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Uhry </PERSON> and won the 1988 Pulitzer Prize for drama. Touring with <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> are <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> as the chauffeur and <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Root </PERSON> as her exasperated son. <PERSON> Uhry </PERSON> modeled the woman after his grandmother, an elementary school teacher. He and <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> talked at length about the woman who died in 1973 at the age of 95. He relayed bits and pieces of the woman's life to give the actress a better understanding of her character. `` For instance, he told me that his grandmother's curiosity was such that when she was reading she always had the dictionary beside her,'' Miss <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> recalls. `` She would look up words she did n't know, be carried away by what she was reading in the dictionary and would end up reading that. Miss Daisy is only the latest in a long parade of characters that the actress has brought to life on stage. She has won five <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> awards for her efforts. She found small jobs in the theater when she first moved to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in the mid-1940s. `` I was sort of a young character actress so there was a niche for me _ the oddball girl,'' she recalls. Miss <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> astonished Broadway in 1950 when she played the lonely 12-year-old tomboy <PERSON> Frankie </PERSON> <PERSON> Addams </PERSON> in <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> <PERSON> McCullers </PERSON>' `` The Member of the Wedding.'' She was 24 at the time. Her co-star was <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> <PERSON> Waters </PERSON> in what many consider her greatest role. `` Ethel Waters was a phenomenon of nature,'' Miss <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> recalls. `` She was like the force of <LOCATION> Niagara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>. I've never experienced that same power from any other actress.'' The next year she won her first <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> award as the amoral hedonist <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowles </PERSON> in `` I Am a Camera,'' adapted from <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Isherwood </PERSON>'s `` Berlin Stories.'' Other Tonys arrived for her portrayals of <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> of Ark in `` The Lark,'' a 40-year-old divorcee falling for a younger man in `` Forty Carats,'' <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> in `` The Last of Mrs. <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>'' and poet <PERSON> Emily </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> in `` The Belle of <LOCATION> Amherst </LOCATION>.'' Miss <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> carries on in the old tradition of such acting greats as <ORGANIZATION> Katharine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Lunt </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Fontanne </PERSON>, performers who go out on the road with their shows. `` I guess nothing could intimidate me anymore because I did ` The Belle of <LOCATION> Amherst </LOCATION>' for so long in huge barns, in tiny theaters, in middle-size theaters and on basketball floors,'' she adds. `` I even did six weeks of one-night stands,'' Miss <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> says. `` There was no time to adjust. You just slap the makeup on and do it. Some antenna tells you: ` too much voice' or ` too little voice.''' That instinct for acting was born early. `` I once heard an interview with <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> who said both his parents loved the theater and so he ` inherited the wish,''' she says. `` That was his expression. I think I did, too, because both my parents adored the theater and took us to the theater and talked about the theater.'' By the time she was 14, she knew she wanted to be an actress. `` My parents were very tolerant,'' she says. `` I do n't think they took it seriously, although I did.'' Miss <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> still does, even after more than four decades of acting. `` I try to be adventurous, especially in rehearsal,'' she says. `` I must try it, and something will happen from trying it, even if what I'm doing does n't succeed. I've learned the value in saying ` yes' to everything. Eventually, you may have to say ` no,' but say ` yes' first.'' That sense of adventure extends to looking for new works, too. Today, she spends a lot of time reading scripts. `` Now I've taken an idea for a play to the Long Wharf Theater -LRB- in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION> -RRB- and they've commissioned it to be written for <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> Robards </PERSON> and me,'' Miss <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> says. `` The play's about <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> and his wife. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Freed </PERSON> will write it, but I wo n't be able to do it until late next summer at the very earliest. But then, part of the excitement of life is to work on something new.''
