<HEAD>Story Behind `Diamond Trap' Almost as Intriguing as Mystery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` The Diamond Trap,'' which leads off the season for the `` CBS Sunday Movie'' on Sept. 25, has career risks, corporate intrigue, tragedy and triumph. And a lot of it took place before the cameras rolled. The movie stars <PERSON> Brooke </PERSON> <PERSON> Shields </PERSON>, Twiggy, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hesseman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Marinaro </PERSON>, but the gold stars for putting it all together go to the executive producer, <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>, a former publicist and top <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> agent who boosted the careers of such performers as <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> and <PERSON> Farrah </PERSON> <PERSON> Fawcett </PERSON>, is not likely to produce `` The <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Story </PERSON>.'' It would be too easy. Big script, big stars, lots of easy production money. Instead, <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> took a regulation thriller based on the novel `` The Great Diamond Robbery'' from mystery novelist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Minahan </PERSON> and insisted on Miss Shields and <PERSON> Twiggy </PERSON> as the female leads for the script, which had been revised eight times over 2 -LCB- years by writer <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Peckinpah </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> claims one of the best industry records for television movies, with the seven he has done so far averaging a 33 share, and none lower than a 31 share, the term used by <PERSON> A.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON> to describe the percentage of the overall TV audience viewing a particular show. He knows how to hit the right audience buttons or, in his words, `` Put the sizzle in the steak.'' But wanting Miss Shields for the part and getting her were two different things. He made a point of going to this year's `` People's Choice'' awards to put the script in her hand. The role for Miss Shields was that of a gallery employee who is part of a plot to steal $ 12 million in jewels, but the police, including <PERSON> Twiggy </PERSON> as a <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Yard detective, persuade her to help them foil the crime. The part of the sophisticated 30-year-old would be the first adult role for <PERSON> Shields </PERSON>, a 23-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> honors graduate. She wanted it. But not everyone wanted her. She had to read for the role, for <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>, for director <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, for <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> and for <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>, an unusual demand on someone who has already commanded major film roles. `` Certain people involved in the production were so worried about how to deal with a, quote, ` movie star' on a 22-day shooting schedule that the final compromise was to put part of my salary in escrow,'' said <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> in an interview. `` If there was a problem, the first money to be lost would be mine. `` I told <PERSON> Brooke </PERSON> I was going to do this and she said, ` Do n't worry, I wo n't let you down,''' he said `` Not only did she not let me down, she made me very proud. She is one of those people ... who everybody waits for to fail. And she's succeeded,'' said <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>. He called Miss Shields `` easy to work with and able to turn in a fine performance, even with all this pressure on her.'' There were other perils. The project came to <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> just as the network leadership was going through a shakeup, with <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> leaving the network and <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> LeMasters </PERSON> replacing him. `` It was about to be caught between the switches,'' said <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>. `` There was something CBS wanted from me, and it was hard to give, but I went in and gave it to them,'' said <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>. He did n't identify the sacrifice, but most likely it was a different movie or series project. `` And then I asked them for a favor afterward. ` Please let me do this and I wo n't let you down.' And now it's their leadoff movie,'' <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> said. But even after getting a green light, there was the matter of financing.. `` The problem was the picture was too expensive to make,'' <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> said `` This picture was filmed in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION>, Bath, <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, with four major stars, each of whom could be star of their own TV movie.'' In the midst of grappling with finances, <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>'s father, <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON>, died of complications from a heart condition April 17. <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> has dedicated the movie to his father. `` At the time my father died, the picture was falling apart,'' <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> recalled. `` On the day of my father's funeral, a person from <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> said to me, ` Do n't worry, it's going to work out.' And another person from <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> said the same thing. And they did it. `` That means there are people functioning in these corporations. They do n't get an opportunity very often to express their emotions, because everything is the bottom line. But I've seen CBS and <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> come through big, twice,'' said <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>. He also got the studio and the network to restore the `` Mike Hammer'' series to the air after star <PERSON> Stacy </PERSON> <PERSON> Keach </PERSON> was imprisoned in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> on cocaine charges. `` The Diamond Trap'' faces the Olympics on <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and probably a broadcast of the movie `` Romancing the Stone'' on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, so <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> knows he will not match the previous shares he has gained for television movies. `` Whatever I get -LRB- in ratings share -RRB-, I would have gotten only half of it without these two women,'' <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> said.
