<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Eight Men Out''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 It seems unthinkable today that a major league baseball team could conspire to throw the World Series. But it happened in 1919. `` Say it ai n't so, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON>,'' were the words that echoed through history when the infamous `` Black Sox Scandal'' was mentioned. Writer-director <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sayles </PERSON> takes his cue from that line spoken by a young boy in fashioning `` Eight Men Out,'' a movie that is incisive, touching and instructive without appearing to be a history lesson. As the tragedy of the scandal unfolds, two young boys who idolized the players and cadged dimes to buy tickets to games become symbolic of the baseball fans whose dreams were tied to the champion <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION> team that seemed a shoo-in to beat the <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION> in the World Series. We meet the players at the height of their success, a team with the grace of ballet dancers, the naivete of children and the winning force of a steamroller. Hailed by the media and worshiped by fans, they are in constant conflict with the team's stingy owner, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Comiskey </PERSON>, a fine bad guy portrayal by <PERSON> Clifton </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON>. When sleazy gamblers including the infamous <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothstein </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Lerner </PERSON> -RRB- propose `` fixing'' the World Series, most team members are vulnerable. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Strathairn </PERSON> is a memorable example as <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Cicotte </PERSON>, the aging pitcher who is denied a bonus and agonizes over selling out for his family's sake. In true ensemble form, all of the performances are top rate. D.B. <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON> is touching as the talented country boy <PERSON> Shoeless </PERSON> <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> whose inability to read or write makes him prey to corrupting pressures. It is he who turns away sadly from the child's plaint, `` Say it ai n't so, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON>.'' As the fix sets in, we see the expert players expertly losing game after game. In the press box, journalist <PERSON> Ring </PERSON> <PERSON> Lardner </PERSON>, coolly portrayed by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sayles </PERSON> himself, and <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Fullerton </PERSON>, adeptly played by <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> writer <PERSON> Studs </PERSON> <PERSON> Terkel </PERSON>, become sadly aware that the team, soon to be derisively tagged `` The <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION>,'' has been corrupted. The case leads to formation of the baseball commission and appointment of the first commissioner, Judge <PERSON> Kenesaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Mountain </PERSON> <PERSON> Landis </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> -RRB- who punished all involved team members _ even those who did n't actively participate in the scam _ by barring them from professional baseball forever. This is a must-see film for baseball fans and an instructive entertainment for the rest of us. As writer, director and actor, <PERSON> Sayles </PERSON> hits three home runs. `` Eight Men Out'' is rated PG.
</TEXT>
