<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Just Before the Bullets Fly'' -LRB- Epic -RRB- _ The <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> <PERSON> Allman </PERSON> Band Fans of the <ORGANIZATION> Allman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> wo n't be disappointed with founding brother <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON>'s latest solo effort, which echoes the patented Southern sound of the original group and paints a lyrical portrait of a rocker who has survived. <PERSON> Allman </PERSON>'s bouts with various chemicals are well-known, and on `` Just Before the Bullets Fly'' he deals with that image right off the bat. The first cut, `` Demons,'' has him singing, `` But oh, he's got his demons @ And they stay right by his side @ Through his everyday hell, yeah. Later, on `` Oceans Awash the <LOCATION> Gunwale </LOCATION>,'' he credits the music itself for saving him: `` Once more we're cheating on the reaper @ With all the gypsy still in our souls @ Cause I know there's a God up there somewhere @ Who must love rock and roll.'' And it's the music, particularly <PERSON> Allman </PERSON>'s throaty blues vocals, that keeps `` Just Before the Bullets Fly'' interesting. Guitarist <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Toler </PERSON>, formerly of <PERSON> Dicky </PERSON> <PERSON> Betts </PERSON>' Great Southern band, is the other major creative force here. His blues-rock licks are predictable: lots of long, ringing guitar solos that recall <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON>'s late brother, <PERSON> Duane </PERSON> <PERSON> Allman </PERSON>. But it's become a classic sound and <PERSON> Toler </PERSON> pays homage well. The title song, `` Demons,'' `` Ca n't Get Over You'' and a new version of `` Every Hungry Woman'' are vintage Allman-style blues. And <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> sings with a power and range you wo n't find on anything he's done since `` Eat a Peach.'' A couple of other songs fail. An attempt at jazz-rock, `` Thorn and a Wild Rose,'' sinks beneath the weight of its wash of synthesizers and mushy metaphorical lyrics. And a pop song, `` Night Games,'' forces <PERSON> Allman </PERSON> to try to sing bouncily _ and that's not his strength. But the rollicking, guitar-piano-and-organ sound that fans of the original <ORGANIZATION> Allmans </ORGANIZATION> know by heart, is alive and kicking on `` Just Before the Bullets Fly.'' And so is a rock' n' roll warrior, <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> <PERSON> Allman </PERSON>. _ By <PERSON> Curt </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Big Dreams in a Small Town'' -LRB- RCA -RRB- _ Restless Heart The problem with this kind of country-by-committee approach is that by the time everyone gets through, the result is much like a modern-day political platform _ it sounds nice enough, and it wo n't offend anybody, but it's nothing to inspire the masses With `` Big Dreams in a Small Town,'' Restless Heart gives us an album with 12 songwriters, seven producers, five vocalists, nine songs _ and, as a result, no focus. These five former <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> session players have lodged themselves firmly in the Alabama-Oak Ridge Boys league, with mellow harmonies and professional musicianship. But while those groups have managed to meld into a distinctive identity, Restless Heart too often sounds like that staple of old-style country music shows _ the band playing a couple of tunes before the star takes the stage. `` The Bluest Eyes in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>,'' the current hit off this collection, is as good an example as any. What begins with a nice piano introduction from the classically trained <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Innis </PERSON> soon enough settles into nice harmonies that eventually pull lead singer <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> _ who really can sing _ into a nice vanilla morass. The first half has its moments: <PERSON> Innis </PERSON> with some crafty pop piano on `` Say What's in Your Heart,'' reminiscent of the early <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Joel </PERSON>; and a solid group effort on the title cut, a quintessential example of country pop. But things start to get a little adventurous in the second half, and not to good effect, either: a crowded swamp-Western-Indian air-of-mystery motif for `` <LOCATION> Eldorado </LOCATION>,'' and an unfortunate try at funkiness in `` This Time.'' With so many talented singers running around, Restless Heart still needs to find its voice _ or at least a chairman of the board. _ By <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` The Hits'' -LRB- Epic -RRB- _ <PERSON> REO </PERSON> <PERSON> Speedwagon </PERSON> <PERSON> REO </PERSON> <PERSON> Speedwagon </PERSON> has several strikes against it: banal lyrics, bland musicianship, the lack of a distinctive band personality. But they are unpretentious about their abilities _ no concept albums, no `` save the world'' singles, no 20-minute guitar solos. They just try to make hit singles and have often succeeded. The songs on `` Greatest Hits'' are at worst, uninteresting, and at best, instantly hummable. <PERSON> REO </PERSON> <PERSON> Speedwagon </PERSON> has lasted 20 years with only a couple of personnel changes, and the songs on `` Greatest Hits'' date from 1973 to the present. The band's limitations and strengths are typified by lead singer <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON>. He is n't terribly soulful, but <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> does n't pretend to have a great voice and he handles fast songs and ballads equally well. The three best songs come from 1980's best-selling `` Hi Infidelity'': `` Keep on Loving You,'' `` Take It on the Run'' and `` Do n't Let Him Go.'' All have strong melodies and plenty of harmonies. They do n't hold up under close listening but sound good on the radio and the beach. Also included are the earlier singles, `` Time for Me to Fly'' and `` Roll With the Changes,'' and their most recent hits, `` Ca n't Fight This Feeling,'' and `` That Ai n't Love. _ By <PERSON> Hillel </PERSON> <PERSON> Italie </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
