<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Harlem Comes to Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YOKOHAMA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> street artist <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> the Great bebops a bit as he daubs the finishing touches on the belt of a dancing woman gyrating across a construction site fence. As he brings his own brand of <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaskin </PERSON> is completely oblivious to the trucks roaring past, the summer sun and the sweat beads streaking the lenses of his glasses. `` Nothing you do for love or beauty gon na die,'' he says, his arms spreading wide to take in a 100-foot mural of black men and women caught in the motions of the samba, the jitterbug and the bump. `` I know the Japanese have a different picture of blacks. I want them to understand the black people and their world.'' It's an intoxicating vision for a self-taught artist, a sailor's son who spent his boyhood in silence after a fall rendered him mute for 12 years To fill the void, <PERSON> Gaskin </PERSON> turned to art. After he recovered his speech he moved to <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION>, where a decade ago he decorated his first storefront riot grate. The depiction of a magnolia _ his `` Japanese blossom tree'' _ was the germination of the kind of greatness to which a lonely boy aspired. The work led to calls from other storekeepers _ more than 150 so far _ and a sort of international following after foreign travelers began touring <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION>'s avenues. <PERSON> Gaskin </PERSON> has demonstrated his technique before African art classes and painted murals for French municipalities. In July, he arrived in this <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> port city, summoned by Japanese developers who liked his raw style. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Grand </PERSON>, as his paint-spattered coveralls proclaim, was charged with injecting American-style verve into a neglected suburb selected as the site for an international shopping district. `` We chose <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> because he's very good for wall paintings,'' said <PERSON> Tatsuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Nannichi </PERSON>, a publicist for the <ORGANIZATION> Honmoku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION>. `` He worked in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, also <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, and he's a very international person. I think he's the symbol of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.'' The Panamanian-born <PERSON> Gaskin </PERSON> has a theme he calls `` Harmony Among the Races.'' It has been a dream to paint it in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, where he hopes to find sponsors who will provide a more permanent backdrop. `` When we look at racism, in my world I'm dealing with black and white, but never with yellow, never with brown people, red people,'' he says. `` Black and white is a contrast. But it takes three or more colors to make harmony. And since <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is a most powerful nation, I figure it takes <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to link a lot of people around the world.'' The project must wait until his next visit. For now, <PERSON> Gaskin </PERSON> is happy that he's made a start. `` I planted a seed in <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> and now the seed has grown into a beautiful tree,'' he said. `` I wanted <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to share a little bit of the black culture.'' After two weeks' work, <PERSON> Gaskin </PERSON>'s charcoal outlines were filled with browns, oranges and magentas set off by a sky-blue backdrop. His section of corrugated steel canvas runs along a four-lane thoroughfare, side by side with other temporary murals by Japanese artists and art students. In <PERSON> Gaskin </PERSON>'s painted world, everyone is smiling. Silver sparks fly from tambourines, elbows jut, hands clap, a good bit of thigh shows as a chubby lady twirls her skirt. `` I do n't know art well, but I feel this is live <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> modern art. Fantastic,'' said <PERSON> Kazuhiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Kitagawa </PERSON>, a bank clerk and <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> fan. `` I saw his art in <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> last year, and I met him. He was wearing the same clothes.'' On a recent Sunday, <PERSON> Gaskin </PERSON> presented a Franco Award to one of the Japanese art students. Standing on a cloth-covered box in his coveralls, his 6-foot-5 frame crowned by a colorful straw hat from a nearby festival, <PERSON> Gaskin </PERSON> read the proclamation in stumbling Japanese to the student, who shook his hand and scurried away. `` Japanese artists will get incentive from his art,'' <PERSON> Kitagawa </PERSON> said. `` If Japanese paint, it becomes imitation. He is real art.''
