<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: The Personal Touch for Musical Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If the musical gods were to prophesize that a black woman who sang heart-tugging folk ballads would top the charts in 1988, you'd figure it would be a very good year for <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Armatrading </PERSON>. After all, whoever heard of <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>? But no one ever said the gods were fair. <PERSON> Armatrading </PERSON>, whose name frequently comes up when critics talk about <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>'s work, is still searching for that elusive hit 15 years and 13 albums into her recording career. She quickly brushes off questions about the runaway success of <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>'s debut record, saying she has n't heard her music. A & amp; M Records does n't shy away, however. In advertisements for <PERSON> Armatrading </PERSON>'s new album, `` The Shouting Stage,'' the company says that while hundreds of singers are compared to her, `` hundreds of thousands of her fans knew she was there first.'' The company is banking on the current mini-revival of the singer-songwriter era to give <PERSON> Armatrading </PERSON> a long-sought boost to stardom. `` Personally, I think it's unfair that <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> has n't had the same breaks that <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON> had,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Corson </PERSON>, executive director of product development for A & amp; M. `` It's more of a question of timing. <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> blazed the trails and <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON>'s taken advantage of it.'' Actually, there is n't much to the comparisons between <PERSON> Armatrading </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> beyond the superficial similarities. <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>, in her debut album, features quiet, introspective folk songs about love and society's treatment of the downtrodden. <PERSON> Armatrading </PERSON> sticks to personal politics, her emotionally intense music an often exuberant mixture of rock, reggae, jazz and folk. The songs are so achingly personal that people often assume they're all autobiographical, which would have given <PERSON> Armatrading </PERSON> a pretty full emotional life over the past decade and a half. `` I think of it as a compliment, because the songs are written to be believed,'' she said before one of the early dates in her current <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tour. `` They're generally from something that's happened ... It's just that it's not necessarily from my things. But I write it as if it's about me.'' The new album's title cut comes from a magazine article that theorizes every couple must go through a period of fighting to achieve true intimacy, she said. The song is written in the voice of a woman addressing her lover in the wake of this `` shouting stage,'' her tone veering between resignation and vulnerability. More controversial is `` The Devil I Know,'' a searing indictment of a `` wandering'' man from a woman trying to keep him close to home that's already been taken to heart by many feminists. `` One chap said to me that the difference between men and women is that men can distinguish between lust and love,'' she said. `` A man can have a one-night stand or an affair that lasts a couple of years and feel that he's being quite faithful to his real partner because it's a purely sexual thing. `` It's women who have trouble thinking that if you go to bed with someone you do n't love them,'' she said. `` We'd like the two to go together.'' The song, she said, is about the age-old double standard that seems to accept this behavior from men and condemn it from women. If someone thinks they've happened upon an album of men-bashing, `` The Devil I Know'' is immediately followed by the cheery `` Living for You,'' about the happy side of being wrapped up in a relationship. <PERSON> Armatrading </PERSON>'s live show is packed with playful energy, almost mocking the stereotypes of the singer-songwriter genre. She bounces across the stage and trades some slightly choreographed dance steps with saxophonist <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>. The highlights come when she straps on an acoustic guitar for a bluesy `` -LRB- I Love It When You -RRB- Call Me Names'' and a version of <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>'s `` Moondance.'' Her albums have become progressively harder-edged throughout the 1980s, but `` The Shouting Stage'' quiets things down a bit. It has a highly produced, jazzy sound, benefitting from such studio stars as <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Knopfler </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> of Dire Straits. As much as she liked it at the time, <PERSON> Armatrading </PERSON> said she ca n't listen to her 2-year-old album `` Sleight of Hand'' without pulling the needle from the vinyl Some of the songs, she admits, she finds `` irritable.'' `` I was trying to write an album that I hope in a couple of years' time people can sit and listen to just as much as they do today,'' she said. Her record company will settle for people listening to it now. <PERSON> Corson </PERSON> said he's encouraged by the company's sales performance in the first few weeks of its release, though disappointed by radio's continued reluctance `` I think it's a time of opportunity for us,'' he said.
</TEXT>
