<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: Turning Best Sellers Into Hot TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On the seventh floor of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Mayfair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION>, actress <PERSON> Lindsay </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> was preparing the climactic scene in the TV movie `` Voice of the Heart.'' The one-time `` Bionic Woman'' faced a difficult moment: She must persuade her on-screen lover, <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickson </PERSON> -RRB-, that her past actions are less hateful than they once seemed. `` Do you need holding?'' asked director <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Wharmby </PERSON>. <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> nodded `` yes,'' and <PERSON> Wharmby </PERSON> walked over to bolster her confidence by hugging her. The scene is a buildup to the confession on which hangs the plot of <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON>'s 1983 best-selling novel, whose TV version will be aired in two 2-hour segments this winter over <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> and in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on a network that has not yet been announced. The $ 8 million movie promises all the ingredients of high-class soap opera: a web of romance and deception, exotic foreign locations, and an emotionally storm-tossed heroine named <PERSON> Katharine </PERSON> <PERSON> Tempest </PERSON>, played by <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>. `` Voice of the Heart'' is the third <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> book to be adapted for the screen. She began writing 40 years ago at the age of 12 when, as a youngster in an upper middle-class family in <LOCATION> Leeds </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, she sold her first story about a girl and her horse to a children's magazine `` I think my destiny was sealed,'' she recalled in an interview. However, her writing was put on hold while she set out to experience life. `` I do n't think you can earn a living at the age of 16 writing novels.'' In her eagerness to gain that knowledge, she shunned college and became a typist at the <ORGANIZATION> Yorkshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evening </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. She was promoted to cub reporter in six months. A year later, at age 18, she became women's page editor and by age 20 moved to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s renowned newspaper row, Fleet Street. She married American film producer <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> in 1963 and moved to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. At the time, she was writing a syndicated column on interior design that ran in 185 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> newspapers. However, the desire to write fiction began to nudge her. She started her first novel in 1970, and had started three others by 1975. Then came `` A Woman of Substance,'' which she called the story of `` a strong woman who makes it in a man's world when women were not doing that.'' `` When I started to write those initial pages, I really felt very excited because I somehow knew in my bones ... this was the book I was going to finish and the book that would be right,'' she said. The hardcover version has sold more than 11 million copies since 1979, and the paperback topped <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> best-seller list for 43 weeks. It also was made into an acclaimed syndicated TV miniseries. Her second, `` Voice of the Heart,'' sold 2.5 million copies in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Her third, `` Hold the Dream,'' was also a best seller. `` Voice of the Heart'' co-stars <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Brolin </PERSON> as the dashing actor-director <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> and <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON> <PERSON> Tennant </PERSON> as <PERSON> Francesca </PERSON> <PERSON> Cunningham </PERSON> <PERSON> Avery </PERSON>, the historical biographer who vies with actress <PERSON> Katharine </PERSON> for <PERSON> Victor </PERSON>'s affections. `` There's a whole person in there, and the person's hurting,'' said the 39-year-old <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> in an interview halfway through the 10-week shooting schedule. `` I've got to humanize her, to make her emotionally accessible to people,'' she said, looking sleeker and more composed than she would later that afternoon when she donned a bathrobe to play the frazzled <PERSON> Katharine </PERSON>. `` She's a very exaggerated kind of character in the fact that she's eccentric and neurotic. ... In the story, if we do n't sympathize with her, then there's no pay-off at the end. <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON> <PERSON> Tennant </PERSON> said she was drawn to the premise of the film. `` The drama pivots on a white lie that is told that seems harmless to the liar and yet devastates the lives of everyone involved,'' said the soft-spoken English actress. `` I think it's quite telling,'' she said of the plot idea. `` When you think of all the information that is being thrown at you and how you deal with it, you think, `` That's not impossible. You could hear something and it could change your life.''' `` Voice of the Heart'' is a contemporary drama, said the elegantly coiffed <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON>, whose `` A Woman of Substance'' and `` Hold the Dream'' also were made into TV movies. They dealt with the department store dynasty of <PERSON> Emma </PERSON> <PERSON> Harte </PERSON>, and starred <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerr </PERSON>. `` It's very up-to-date; it's got a touch of the present,'' she said. `` Katharine is one of those strange, mixed-up weird women.'' Like <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> insisted that <PERSON> Katharine </PERSON> arouse sympathy. `` She's not a bitch,'' the writer said. `` She's a complex and complicated woman and a marvelous actress, who has this frigidity which all goes back to the time when she was molested as a child.'' Although her novels have been filmed and a fourth, `` Act of Will,'' is to follow, <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> said: `` If I wrote a book with the ultimate goal of a TV or movie screen, I think I'd be cheating the reader. `` I'm actually competing with TV because I want to hold the reader. I do n't want the reader saying, ` Oh, This is just a lot of dialogue. I ca n't visualize any of it; I'm going to turn on ` War and Remembrance.''' She insists on having her husband as executive producer on all her TV adaptations. `` A lot of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> producers buy a best seller, keep the title and throw the contents away,'' she said. `` <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> believes you put on-screen the story that's in between those two covers.''
