<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Soviet Singers Spread Patriotic, Religious
Message</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DICKSON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Russian gospel singers are spreading a message of Christianity and speaking out against communism, which they say drove them from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Pankratz </PERSON> and his brother <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> are leaders of the six-member, gospel-rock band <PERSON> Ruscha </PERSON>. The slick, hard-driving group is on the road doing 150 concerts a year, playing mainly for youngsters who hear 90 minutes of rousing music and then 15 minutes of religious and patriotic messages. `` We are cruising across <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, grabbing people by the neck and saying, ` Wake up. You've got it good but you are taking your freedom for granted and you should n't do that. One day you may wake up and be under persecution yourself,''' said 31-year-old <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON>. `` People do n't believe that will happen,'' he said. `` But we grew up under communism, and we have a very great fear of it spreading across the world.'' The brothers said their family was persecuted in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for being Christians and attending underground churches. In 1963, they said, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> secret police came to their house and took their grandfather away. `` He was dragged out in the deep snow in his pajamas,'' said 29-year-old <PERSON> Peter </PERSON>. `` He pointed toward heaven, meaning he'd see us again. That's the last time we saw him. He arrived in a casket two months later. He had frozen to death in <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>.'' The two said their family of eight, after four years of negotiation, paid $ 3,000 a person to leave the country in 1974 and relocate in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, where an aunt lived. `` There's no way to leave unless you sell everything you have,'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> said. `` We sold the only cow we had, the chickens we had, the pigs we had. We sold our house and other people pitched in and helped us financially.'' From <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the brothers came to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on student visas, <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> in 1978, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> a year later. Learning English without formal lessons, they studied at the Word of Life bible institute in upstate <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for a year. They then enrolled at <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lynchburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, where they received undergraduate degrees. `` He really helped us out,'' <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> said about <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON>. `` We did n't know anything about <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. He kind of took us under his wing. Our whole life in this country started right there. We sang in his church and on his TV show. He financed an album and got us into his school.'' The two have since decided to make their home in <LOCATION> Dickson </LOCATION>, about 40 miles west of <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>. They first began performing under the name <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> but learned that the name had a bad connotation in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Because of the name, their touring bus was vandalized several times. `` We got fed up and did something about it,'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> said. `` Americans do n't realize there could be good Russians.'' They changed the spelling to <PERSON> Ruscha </PERSON>. The two-year-old band now consists of the brothers plus Americans <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Denton </PERSON>, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Beck </PERSON>. Their debut album, `` Come Alive,'' was released earlier this year. Their first single is `` Come Home,'' which has been No. 1 on the gospel-rock charts in many cities. Their concerts are mostly in auditoriums and some in churches. `` We play some places no one else goes,'' <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> said. `` People are getting to know us. That's pretty good. `` We want to get a message across through our music. It's a vehicle. We try to tell the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people that people do n't know what it's like under communism. Also, we'd like to educate them that it's a dangerous thing and that there is an answer to life: God. `` What we are trying to do is what a lot of people of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> are failing to do: be able to grab kids' attention and say, ` Do n't be a lazy bum Support your government. Support your country. Stand up for the rights of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.' `` If we're able to change the young people's attitude toward the country, change their lifestyle away from drugs and alcohol and sex and homosexuality, then I think we've done a whole lot more good than 99 percent of the churches in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' The brothers are not <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens, but this is a goal. `` We'd love that more than anything else,'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
