<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Sept. 8, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Human Safety Trials Underway For AIDS Decoy Drug</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first human trials have begun to test the safety and proper dose of an experimental drug that may act as a decoy to attract the deadly AIDS virus and prevent it from invading human blood cells. About 50 patients with acquired immune deficiency syndrome or the less severe AIDS-related complex are participating in the six-month studies of the drug, called rCD4, that began last month at <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Deaconess </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. Tests of the drug's effectiveness against AIDS will begin only after the safety and dosage trials are complete, the researchers said. The drug is a manufactured version of CD4, a protein on the surface of white blood cells, the main targets of the AIDS virus. The virus infects white blood cells by latching onto the CD4 protein. Scientists hope injected rCD4 molecules might act as decoys so AIDS virus particles in a patient's blood latch onto the rCD4 instead of real CD4 on white blood cells. In that way, the drug might slow the virus' ability to spread from cell to cell, thereby slowing or halting the progression of AIDS in an infected person. It also might prevent white blood cells from being infected if it is given immediately after a person has gotten the virus in the bloodstream.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Aerial, Satellite Photos Can Locate Homes For Endangered Birds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Satellite images and aerial photographs can provide a cheap way of finding <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> islands suitable as new homes for endangered birds, a researcher says. <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>, a graduate student in geography at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION>, said by using aerial photos and computer-processed satellite images of the <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> she could distinguish tropical forest, swamp, brushland, fern thickets and cultivated areas. Such information can be used to determine which isolated, uninhabited islands are suitable for reintroduction and successful reproduction of endangered birds, <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> said. Habitat information is prohibitvely expensive to obtain from field studies because because islands are spread over millions of square miles of the western <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, she said. Aerial photos of the <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> can be bought for $ 2,500. Where aerial photos do n't exist, satellite images can be bought for about 10 times that amount, but that's still cheaper than conducting on-the-ground field studies or new aerial surveys, she said. In the past 2,000 years, <LOCATION> Polynesian </LOCATION> hunters eliminated or sharply reduced populations of many land birds from many islands in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>. `` That is no longer a problem, but the remaining birds are threatened by habitat destruction as well as introduced predators, particularly cats, rats and mongeese,'' said <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>, who hopes to protect endangered species by reintroducing them on uninhabited islands where they once thrived. <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> outlined her study Aug. 16 at an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Biological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> meeting.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Permanent Voice Damage Can Result If Minor Laryngeal Injuries</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Untreated
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Experiments on voice boxes removed from cadavers suggest that minor injuries to the larnyx may cause permanent damage to the voice if left untreated. Car crashes, chokeholds, strangleholds and other blunt-force injuries often cause minor fractures to the cartilage framework of the larynx, or voice box, which contains the vocal cords. Such fractures usually are n't treated unless they interefere with breathing, said Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON>, an assistant professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>. However, <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> said his study suggests such fractures can `` cause long-term hoarseness or limit the range of pitch and pitch control.'' The fractures, while difficult to diagnose, can be detected by CAT scans and treated by intricate surgery in which wires are inserted into the voice box to restore proper alignment of cartilage, <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> said. In the <ORGANIZATION> USC </ORGANIZATION> study, voice boxes were removed from five dead people and mounted on a special apparatus, both in their normal condition and after minor injuries were simulated. Warm, humid air was passed through the voice boxes in a manner similar to that in which a person speaks. Analysis showed that even minor fractures reduced the efficiency of each larynx in regulating air flow during the production of sound, suggesting more laryngeal fractures should be treated than is customary, <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
