<HEAD>Dollar Declines In Moderate Trading; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: PRECEDE LONDON, BC</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar declined against most major currencies Tuesday pushed down by a wave of selling after the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency market reopened following the Labor Day weekend. Gold prices also fell after a mixed performance overseas. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said gold was bid at $ 426.60 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $ 429 late Friday. Currency brokers said activity in the foreign-exchange market slowed with the dollar trading in a narrow range following Friday's selloff in advance of the holiday weekend Friday's activity was sparked by a higher-than-expected unemployment figure that showed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy may be weakening. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported unemployment rose 5.6 percent in August, from 5.4 percent in July. Friday's selloff was followed by a further weakening of the dollar in foreign markets Monday, while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency markets were closed. Analysts said after last week's activity, investors were turning their attention to this week's report on the Producer Price Index, an important measure of inflation, and next Wednesday's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit figures. `` The dollar market will be a side market until then,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbanel </PERSON>, first vice president with <ORGANIZATION> Gruntal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. Inc. in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Traders said the markets are likely to remain cautious in advance of the fresh data. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the trading day begins, the dollar fell 0.43 yen to a closing 135.60 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 135.68 yen. At the end of the trading day in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar was down 0.85 yen at 134.925 yen. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost $ 1.7035 to buy one pound, almost two cents more than $ 1.6860 late Monday. Later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound fetched $ 1.70365, compared with $ 1.6850 late Friday. Other late-dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> compared with levels late Friday included: 1.84015 West German marks, down from 1.8524; 1.5530 Swiss francs, down from 1.5567; 1.23405 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2355; 6.2695 French francs, down from 6.2915; 1,378.00 Italian lire, down from 1,381.50. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Monday: 1.8425 West German marks, down from 1.8555; 1.5525 Swiss francs, down from 1.5625; 6.2715 French francs, down from 6.3124; 2.0820 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0957; 1,377.65 Italian lire, down from 1,380.50; 1.2340 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2338. Gold rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 428.10 a troy ounce, compared with late Monday's $ 427.50 per ounce. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold closed at a bid $ 428.00 an ounce compared with $ 427.50 late Monday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell 23 cents to close at a bid $ 429.15 an ounce. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold closed at $ 426.70 a troy ounce compared with $ 429.30 late Friday. Silver bullion prices rose on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market where the metal was trading at a late bid price of $ 6.56 a troy ounce, compared with Monday's $ 6.50. On the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Comex </LOCATION>, silver for current delivery fell to $ 6.485 per troy ounce, compared with Friday's $ 6.518.
