<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-Cocoa     09-06 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Cocoa,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocoa Consumers Ask Producers To Pay Debts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nations that consume cocoa appealed Tuesday to countries that produce it to pay their debts to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>'s fund to stabilize falling world prices. The organization, composed of 37 cocoa consuming and producing nations, faces a shortfall in covering operating costs in the cocoa year that runs from October 1988 to September 1989, said delegates to the cartel's two-week conference, which opened Monday. Cocoa-producing nations owe almost $ 70 million to the group's price-stabilization fund The biggest debtor is the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, which owes $ 48 million. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> owes $ 9 million. Other debtors include <LOCATION> Cameroon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> on Tuesday paid a separate $ 146,700 it owed to the group's administrative fund, said its chief delegate <PERSON> Lindenberg </PERSON> <PERSON> Sette </PERSON>. The shortfall in the price-stabilization fund would also leave the organization unable to finance a proposed new stockpiling scheme aimed at supporting prices, now at their lowest for seven years. Operating costs for 1988-89 are estimated at $ 23 million. The organization estimates it will have only $ 10 million to $ 12 million on hand when the new cocoa year starts Oct. 1. The organization may sell cocoa from its current stockpile of 250,000 metric tons to meet the budget shortfall. The organization's secretariat has drawn up plans to sell 10,000 tons in 1989 and 15,000 in 1989-90.
