<HEAD>Car and Truck Sales Fall 10.7 Percent, Incentives Why</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Edd in 5th graf is correct.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Car and truck sales fell 10.7 percent in August, compared with the same month last year when incentives called for quicker buying decisions by consumers, the automakers and analysts said Tuesday. Foreign and domestic vehicle makers, except <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sales </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said they sold 1.25 million cars and trucks last month, compared with 1.35 million during the same month last year. For the 10-day period ending Aug. 31, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said its sales of U.S.-made cars inched up 2.6 percent compared with the same period last year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, meantime, said its car sales for the period fell 1.4 percent and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported a 13.9 percent drop. Each of the Big Three reported increases in car sales so far this calendar year. <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Edd </PERSON> <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> said a dealer incentive program that stretched through the Labor Day weekend delayed computation of the company's monthly figures. <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Kade </PERSON> said Tuesday that figures for the month had n't been calculated. Both automakers said their sales figures would be announced Wednesday. `` The kinds of incentives that are on this year are normal run-of-the-mill incentives that have been on the cars for a long time,'' said auto analyst <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> DeScenza </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` There's no incentive to buy now to take advantage of current incentives,'' he said. A year ago, car makers offered attractive incentives, including cut-rate financing as low as 1.9 percent for <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> vehicles, to lure customers into showrooms and shrink inventories with just one month left in the model year. Those incentives frequently involved short-term offers such as low financing and cash-back deals. This year the incentives are different. `` The incentives are sustainable kinds of things,'' <PERSON> DeScenza </PERSON> said. `` Incentives have a big impact when it's clear to the car buyer that they are not going to be around very long. `` Everybody knew -LRB- last year -RRB- they were temporary,'' he added, `` that they would n't last forever. Everybody knew that the models that qualified for them were in limited supply and dwindling rapidly.'' <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Grady </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, agreed, saying last year's incentives colored the sales figures this year. `` Certainly we're going to be down -LRB- in sales -RRB- from last year,'' he said. `` These are certainly very strong sales.'' <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> showed declines in late-August and monthly sales while <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> showed increases during the two periods. There were nine selling days in both late-August periods and 27 sales days in August of this year, compared with 26 in August of 1987. For the Aug. 21-31 period this year, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> said it sold 32,214 cars made in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, 2.6 percent higher than the 31,388 it sold during the same period last year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> sold 65,600 U.S.-made cars during the period, a 1.4 percent decrease from the 66,515 cars it sold during the same time last year. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s late-August sales fell from 126,629 last year to 108,986 this year, a drop of 13.9 percent. For the month, the No. 1 automaker sold 284,056 cars, off 20.7 percent from 345,098 in August 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s monthly sales dropped 6.2 percent from 182,824 in August 1987 to 178,023 last month. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> showed the only monthly gain among the Big Three, rising from 75,156 U.S.-made cars in August of last year to 82,366 cars last month _ a 5.5 percent increase. `` Chrysler has been more aggressive than the other two in using incentives to stimulate sales ...'' <PERSON> DeScenza </PERSON> said. `` There's an implication that they're buying the sales -LRB- with incentives -RRB-.''
