e full panel on Tuesday ended a day of deliberation by backing the executive's decision and rejecting the Pernod appeal. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Pernod </PERSON> had said it would not be prepared to act as a `` white knight'' to save Irish Distillers from Grand Met. unless it was pledged the support of 50 percent of Irish Distillers shares. At the weekend it believed it had this support, holding pledges that included one from fruit and vegetable group <ORGANIZATION> FII </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fyffes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> fruit and vegetable merchant, which holds 20 percent of Irish Distillers. But fears that <ORGANIZATION> Fyffes </ORGANIZATION> was about to change its mind and go for the higher English offer led <ORGANIZATION> Pernod </ORGANIZATION> to seek a temporary injunction from the <ORGANIZATION> Dublin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> preventing <ORGANIZATION> Fyffes </ORGANIZATION> from selling to Grand Met. A full hearing of the case will take place Wednesday. <PERSON> Pernod </PERSON> says it admits the Fyffes promise was not in writing, but believes it to be legally enforceable. Irish Distillers products include Irish whiskey brands <ORGANIZATION> Jamesons </ORGANIZATION>, Powers, <PERSON> Paddy </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Tullamore </LOCATION>.
