<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday rejected the appeal by a former vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Litton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> who was convicted of racketeering in a $ 6.3 million defense scheme. <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>, 58, of <PERSON> Drexel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> faces a sentence of three years in prison and a $ 10,000 fine for his participation in one of the largest defense fraud cases ever prosecuted by the government. He was convicted last December of mail fraud, racketeering, obstruction of federal agency proceedings and making false statements to a federal agency. <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> argued in appeal that the evidence against him was insufficient and some testimony was prejudicial. He also argued that he had participated unknowingly in the frauds. However, the appeals court ruled that prosecutors provided ample evidence to convict him. <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, did not return a call for comment. <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> is free on $ 50,000 bail. Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harbist </PERSON> said he plans to file a motion soon asking the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to order <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> to report to prison. In 1986, <ORGANIZATION> Litton </ORGANIZATION> pleaded guilty to more than 300 counts of submitting false claims to the government and 20 counts of mail fraud. <ORGANIZATION> Litton </ORGANIZATION> agreed to pay $ 15 million in fines and resitution. Two other officials, former purchasing manager <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> DiLiberto </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Millspaugh </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Litton </ORGANIZATION> controller, have pleaded guilty in the case. The men and the company were accused of overcharging the government $ 6.3 million by inflating costs on contracts for military electronics.
